          "chapterId": "544865f4-7e4f-4548-908c-99d9c32fed14",
          "title": "Scene 3",
          "text": "The apartment held the specific quality of a space that had been lived in and then stopped. Not abandoned — the QSA's forensic team had been through it, and forensic teams left a particular kind of order behind them, the order of people who had moved everything and replaced it with precision and had thereby made the space feel like a reconstruction of itself rather than the thing itself. The furniture was where it had been. The objects were where they had been. The air carried the faint chemical signature of the scanning agents the team had used on the surfaces.\n\nKain stood in the doorway for thirty seconds and looked at the room without moving through it.\n\nThe living area ran left to right — kitchen at the far end, a window facing north toward the river, a desk against the eastern wall, a sofa, a low table. Standard configuration for a fourteen-floor Southbank apartment of this size. Nothing immediately wrong.\n\nHe started at the bookshelf.\n\nThe *Maltese Falcon* was there — a physical paperback, its spine facing out, positioned on the third shelf from the top between a hardbound collection of Chandler stories and a QSA policy manual that Chen had apparently kept at home. The spine faced out. That was correct. The QSA's passive optical record had documented the reversal — the spine turned inward, the title hidden — as one of the eighteen-month anomalies. The forensic team had replaced it spine-out, which was where it had been for nine years before the replacement arrived.\n\nKain pulled it from the shelf.\n\nA left-handed man who read physical books developed specific habits around them. The spine crease — the point where the book had been held open most often — concentrated on the left side of the binding in a left-handed reader, because the left hand carried the book's weight while the right turned pages. The *Maltese Falcon*'s spine crease ran down the right side.\n\nThe replacement had held it in the right hand. For eighteen months, every time it read this book, it had held it in the right hand because the right hand was dominant and the residue — Chen's left-hand dominance, encoded in nine years of muscle memory — had not extended to the grip on a paperback. Too small a habit. Too far below the threshold of the things the replacement had been given to memorize.\n\nHe replaced the book and moved to the bathroom.",
