          "title": "Scene 6",
          "text": "*The document currently under review pertains to a carrier designated CONV-PQ-GEN-549/KAIN-D, currently at 11 operational deployments.*\n\n*Your specific TUBA1A-PQ variant produces a resonance signal 340% cleaner than the median carrier signal. The Sphere's coherence structure, read through your architecture, produces data that no other carrier in the registry can match at equivalent resolution.*\n\n*Projected deployment 12 is scheduled.*\n\nHe read it again.\n\nNot because the meaning required repetition. Because the meaning required the specific, physical duration of a second reading — the time it took for the data to move from the screen through the optic nerve and into the prefrontal cortex where the microtubules were, where the *TUBA1A-PQ* variant was, where the secondary binding site was degrading at a rate the QSA had been measuring for fourteen months and had not told him about, and where the number 11 sat against the number 14 with a gap of three deployments between them and a median of four to seven months between deployment 14 and ICS collapse.\n\nHe had been deployed eleven times.\n\nEmily had the data. Emily had compiled it. Emily had amended the file fourteen months ago, which was when she had recruited him for the current operation, which was his eleventh deployment, which she had known when she recruited him was his eleventh deployment, which meant she had known when she recruited him that the twelfth would push his buffer efficiency below 19% and the thirteenth and fourteenth would follow in the operational sequence she had already planned.\n\nThe file's last amendment date was fourteen months ago.\n\nShe had known for fourteen months.\n\nThe terminal's cache timer ran to zero and the screen went dark.\n\nThe plant room was very quiet. The air handler had completed its cycle. The bypass switch was in its default position. The fibre connection was gone and the terminal was dark and the Fitzroy Node was offline and the QSA's thermal purge had reached junction eleven and there was nothing left in the room to read.\n\nHe stood in the dark for a specific, measured duration — not shock, not grief, not the melodrama of a man confronting his own mortality, but the operational pause of a man updating his model of the environment he was operating in. The model had contained an error. The error was now corrected. The corrected model contained the following data points:\n\nEleven deployments. Buffer at 19% on the next. Emily had the journals. Emily had the file. Emily had recruited him knowing both. The M. Reyes alias pointed to Emily's operational designation. The third step of the cross-reference, which he had now completed, confirmed that the operational history attached to that designation included fourteen months of data on his own degradation.\n\nHe was not an operative running an investigation.\n\nHe was an instrument being calibrated for its twelfth use.\n\nThe sweep team would have a vector in eleven minutes.\n\nHe put the folded paper back in his jacket pocket, moved the HVAC cabinet's side panel back into position, turned the four bolts a quarter-turn each, and walked back through the service corridor to the rear entrance. The heritage oak's canopy covered the lane's middle forty metres. The Axis unit at the lane's entrance logged his exit at the edge of its sightline — a dark jacket, a walking pace, a chin angle that presented the orbital ridge rather than the full face.\n\nA man in a dark jacket.\n\nSmith Street ran north. He walked south.",
