          "text": "The corridor ran forty metres under fluorescent light that had never seen daylight and had developed, in its isolation, a quality that was less illumination than exposure. Every surface it touched looked examined rather than lit. The granite walls. The sealed doors. The back of Emily's jacket as she walked three paces ahead of him, her shoulders carrying the particular set of someone who had been in this building before and had decided, at some prior point, how she felt about it.\n\nKain's right hand was in his jacket pocket. The tremor had started on the drive up the final switchback — not the fragmentation, just the tremor, the low-frequency vibration in the ring and little finger that had become, over four years, as reliable as weather. He kept his hand still by pressing the knuckle of his thumb against the seam of his pocket lining. It worked well enough that nobody had ever commented on it.\n\nThe proximity field pressed against the inside of his skull like a change in altitude. Present, not painful — a reminder that the air in this place was doing something the body had not been designed to accommodate. A reminder that the air in this place was doing something the body had not been designed to accommodate.\n\nEmily stopped at a door marked with a single horizontal stripe of blue tape — the kind of low-tech identifier that existed in high-security facilities because the people who worked in them had learned, through experience, that complex digital signage failed at the worst possible moments. She pressed her palm to the panel. The door opened.\n\n\"Aspect is already inside,\" she said.\n\n\\*\\*\\*  \nThe room held a table, three chairs, and a wall-mounted display that currently showed nothing. A Gen-3 medical scanner occupied the corner — older than the Gen-4 units in the bar, its casing yellowed at the seams, its sensor array pointed at the chair nearest the wall with the patient, indifferent attention of something that had been waiting a long time and had no opinion about the wait.\n\nThe man beside it was not what Kain had expected, though he had not formed a specific expectation. Aspect — the name was a designation, not a surname, the kind of single-word identifier the QSA assigned to personnel whose operational role required a layer of institutional distance between their function and their person — was perhaps sixty, with the lean, careful build of someone who had spent decades in environments where excess was a liability. He wore a QSA medical uniform without insignia. His hands rested on the table in front of him, relaxed, which was the specific relaxation of someone who had delivered difficult information many times and had learned that the body's stillness was a form of professional courtesy.\n\n\"Mr. Kain,\" he said. \"Sit down, please.\"\n\nKain sat. Emily took the chair against the wall, behind and to his left, outside his direct sightline. He did not turn to look at her.\n\n\"I'm going to run a standard biometric intake,\" Aspect said. \"It will take approximately four minutes. I'll explain what I'm looking for as we go.\"\n\n\"You already know what you're looking for,\" Kain said.\n\nAspect's hands did not move. \"Yes.\"\n\n\"Then skip the intake and tell me.\"\n\nA pause. Not long — two seconds, perhaps three. The pause of someone recalibrating the approach.\n\n\"Your PQ genotype,\" Aspect said, \"is a variant we designate Carrier-Proximate. It's present in approximately 0.3 percent of the population. In most carriers, it remains dormant across a full lifespan — the genotype expresses no symptoms, causes no measurable neurological deviation, and is detectable only through targeted genetic sequencing.\" He kept his eyes on Kain's. \"In a small subset of Carrier-Proximate individuals — roughly one in twelve — the genotype activates. We call the activation event the Bleed.\"\n\nThe fluorescent light pressed down on the table between them. Kain's right hand rested in his lap, thumb against the seam of his trouser pocket.\n\n\"The Bleed presents initially as peripheral fragmentation,\" Aspect continued. \"Disruptions in the visual field, typically lasting less than a second. Patients frequently attribute these to fatigue or stress and do not seek assessment.\" He paused. \"Over time, the fragmentation extends. The visual disruptions become longer. They begin to affect other sensory channels — auditory processing, proprioception, the brain's ability to maintain a stable model of its immediate physical environment.\" Another pause. \"In the final stages, the patient's capacity to distinguish between present sensory input and stored neurological pattern breaks down entirely. The brain begins to run on memory rather than perception. The patient is, functionally, no longer present in the room they are standing in.\"\n\nSilence flattened the room. The Gen-3 scanner pointed at the chair with its patient, indifferent attention.\n\n\"How long,\" Kain said.\n\n\"From first presentation of peripheral fragmentation to final-stage cognitive dissolution — the average is six years. The range is four to nine.\" Aspect's hands remained still. \"We would need to establish when your fragmentation first presented to give you a more precise window.\"\n\n\"Four years ago,\" Kain said. \"March. I was in a car park in Fitzroy North. A neon sign broke into its component frequencies for approximately half a second and then reassembled.\"\n\nAspect wrote nothing down. \"Then your window is between now and two years from now, with the median probability clustering around fourteen months.\"\n\nThe number landed with the blunt, undeniable weight of a projectile, stopping every internal process that preceded it.\n\nFourteen months.\n\nNot an estimate. Not a range. A statistical median that erased the complexity of his future and replaced it with a countdown. Two years was a political concession; less than that was a cruelty. Fourteen months was the number his body had already arrived at, quantified and confirmed by a system that had no opinion on the loss.\n\nHe felt the proximity field pressure shift. It ceased to be an external wrongness pressing against his skull and became, instead, a resonance with an internal truth. The tremor in his right hand, which he had been suppressing by pressing his thumb into his pocket seam, now felt like a confirmation, not a failure—the physical signature of his architecture vibrating at a frequency that his body could no longer deny.  \nHe opened his eyes and looked at the fluorescent light. It was no longer examining the room; it was counting the seconds he had left to sit under its sterile glow.\n\nHe had carried this possibility for four years, building his daily architecture around it. The fragmentation, the tremor, the way certain combinations of light and movement could drop him out of the present moment—these were not symptoms he had ignored, but data points he had meticulously filed, calculated, and managed. He had built workarounds—the grip on the glass, the pulse count, the specific route through the Pearl’s car park—because the alternative was to sit in a room exactly like this one and hear a number. The workarounds were an admission that he knew the game was running. The number was the timer going red.\n\nHe turned his head.\n\nEmily sat against the wall with her hands in her lap and her eyes on the middle distance between herself and the table. The masseter tension was gone, replaced by a quality of absolute, controlled absence—the specific expression of someone who had already processed this information and was now managing the fact of having processed it in advance. Her body was a perfectly balanced equation in a moment of catastrophic instability.  \nShe had known.  \nThe realization was a cognitive event, sharp and cold, overriding the residual shock of the diagnosis. She had known before she walked into the Black Pearl. She had known before she sent the file, before she described the elegance of Chen’s absence, before she appealed to his unique ability to read the negative space. She had known, and she had built the operation around it, factoring his impending terminality into the calculus.\n\nThe Varn case had been a professional betrayal: the elimination of his career as a necessary operational cost. This was an existential betrayal: the instrumentalization of his death. She had viewed the fourteen months not as a tragedy, but as a parameter—a variable she had already run the numbers on and decided was acceptable.\n\nThe raw injustice of it did not manifest as anger, but as a cold, analytical certainty. Her betrayal was measurable. It had a clinical application.\n\nHe looked at the empty chair where Aspect had been sitting, then at the sealed door of the room. The air was cold, but the pressure in his skull was rising, the beginning of a Bleed that was emotional, not neurological—a rejection of the architecture she had forced him into.\n\nHe forced his right hand out of his pocket and placed it flat on the table. He did not care if the tremor was visible. The tremor was now part of the truth she had bought.  \nHe turned back to the table. The fluorescent light was a lie. The stillness of the room was a lie. The only truth was the number: Fourteen months, and the woman who had traded it for a clean set of operational logs.\n\n\"What else,\" he said.\n\n\\*\\*\\*  \nAspect left them with the files at 2:40 AM.\n\nThe official record occupied the left side of the table — three folders, their covers stamped with the QSA's classification hierarchy in descending order of access. Emily had legitimate clearance for all of them. She had spread them open before Aspect closed the door, her movements efficient and practiced, the movements of someone who had been in this room with these files before.\n\nThe journals occupied the right side of the table.\n\nThree volumes. Hardbound, A5, their covers a dark green that had faded at the corners to something closer to grey. The spines carried no title — only a sequence of dates in handwriting that was small and precise and slightly left-leaning, the handwriting of someone who had been trained to write quickly and had never entirely lost the speed.\n\nKain picked up the first volume.\n\nThe paper was the kind that absorbed ink rather than holding it on the surface — the slight roughness of a journal bought for use rather than appearance. The first entry was dated fourteen years ago. The handwriting filled the page margin to margin, with no paragraph breaks, the way people write when they are thinking faster than they can organize.\n\n*The insertion window is narrower than the theoretical models suggest. Coherence degrades at the cellular level within 71 hours of initial quantum state transfer — not 96 as the 2128 trials indicated. The discrepancy is in the substrate. We have been modeling against synthetic tissue. The living substrate responds differently. It resists.*\n\nHe turned pages. The entries were not dated consistently — some carried full timestamps, others only a month and year, a few nothing at all. The handwriting remained constant: small, precise, left-leaning, the pen pressed hard enough into the paper that the impressions were visible on the reverse of each page.\n\n*Subject 7 presents the first clean insertion at 68 hours. Behavioral integration is 94% at 72 hours. The remaining 6% is what I have begun calling the residue — the behavioral patterns so deeply encoded in the original subject's neurology that they survive the transfer and surface in the replacement as habits the replacement cannot account for. The replacement does not know why it reaches for the coffee with the left hand. It simply does*.\n\nKain set the volume down. Picked up the second.\n\nThe dates on the second volume's spine placed it four years after the first. The handwriting was the same but the pressure had changed — lighter, the pen moving faster, the letters beginning to compress at the ends of lines as though the writer was running out of space she hadn't anticipated needing.\n\nHe found the entry he was looking for on page forty-three.\n\n*The program has been formally classified under Article 7\\. I have been told this is a protective measure — that classification at this level insulates the research from political interference and ensures continuity regardless of changes in QSA leadership. I have been told this by three separate directors in the past eighteen months. I have begun to count the number of times I am told something is for my protection.*\n\nHe turned to the inside front cover of the second volume.\n\nThe QSA's standard intake protocol required all personal effects removed from a sequestered individual to be logged in the intake manifest — item description, condition, date of removal, authorizing officer. The inside front cover of a journal would carry, if the journal had been processed through intake, a small adhesive label in the upper right corner: a barcode, a manifest reference number, and the date of logging.\n\nThe upper right corner of the inside front cover was clean.\n\nNo label. No barcode. No manifest reference.\n\nHe checked the first volume. Clean.\n\nThe third. Clean.\n\nHe set the third volume down on the table and picked up the nearest official folder — the one on top of the left-hand stack, its cover stamped SOLIS, M. / PERSONAL EFFECTS MANIFEST / INTAKE DATE \\[REDACTED\\]. He opened it to the manifest page.\n\nThe manifest listed forty-seven items. Clothing. Personal electronics, all wiped and archived. One physical photograph, framed. Two books — titles listed. One wristwatch.\n\nNo journals.\n\nThe manifest was complete. The journals were not on it. The journals had never been logged.\n\nEmily sat across the table with the third official folder open in front of her, her eyes moving across the page with the steady, horizontal rhythm of someone reading rather than scanning. Her right hand rested beside the folder. Her left hand was in her lap.\n\nThe masseter tension was absent. Her breathing was even. The folder occupied her complete attention, or performed occupying it, with the same precision she had applied to everything else in this room since Aspect closed the door.\n\nKain closed the manifest folder.\n\nHe picked up the second Solis journal and turned to page forty-four.\n\n*The residue is not a flaw. I have spent three years treating it as an error in the insertion process — a contamination of the replacement's behavioral profile by the original subject's encoded neurology. I was wrong. The residue is the proof. It is the evidence that the original subject existed. It is the thing the replacement cannot erase because it does not know it is there.*\n\n*If you want to find a replacement, you do not look for what is wrong. You look for what is right in a way the replacement cannot explain.*\n\nHe read the entry twice. Then he set the journal down, flat on the table, and looked at the ceiling — at the fluorescent light pressing its examination-quality illumination onto every surface in the room — and he thought about Marcus Chen's left hand going to the right side of the desk for a book that was no longer there.\n\n\"She was right,\" he said.\n\nEmily looked up from the folder. Her eyes moved to the journal, then to his face.\n\n\"About the residue,\" he said. \"Chen's book. The coffee. He wasn't making mistakes. The replacement was carrying Chen's habits without knowing it. The residue.\"\n\n\"Yes,\" Emily said.\n\n\"She worked this out fourteen years ago.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"And the program continued.\"\n\nEmily held his eyes for two seconds. Then she looked back at the folder.\n\nKain picked up the journal.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nHe read for ninety minutes. Emily read beside him, working through the official folders with the methodical patience of someone who had already read them and was reading them again for the specific purpose of reading them in his presence. The room held its fluorescent silence. The Gen-3 scanner pointed at the empty chair.\n\nAt 4:15 AM, he set the third journal down.\n\nThe Bleed had been quiet since Aspect left — no fragmentation, no peripheral stutter, only the tremor in his right hand running its low, reliable frequency. He pressed his thumb against the seam of his pocket and counted his pulse. Sixty-one. The proximity field pressed against the inside of his skull with its altitude-change persistence.\n\nFourteen months, median probability.\n\nHe had two years at the outside. He had fourteen months at the center of the distribution. He had, at the lower bound, less than that — a number Aspect had not stated because stating it would have required a precision that the data did not support and a cruelty that served no operational purpose.\n\nHe had enough time to find the network. He did not have enough time to find it slowly.\n\n\"The residue,\" he said. \"Solis identified it fourteen years ago. The QSA had this information and continued running the program.\"\n\n\"The program was classified under Article 7 before she wrote that entry,\" Emily said. \"The classification meant the research findings were operationally contained. They didn't propagate to the divisions that would have acted on them.\"\n\n\"Who authorized the Article 7 classification?\"\n\nEmily closed the folder in front of her. Her hands rested on its cover, flat, still.\n\n\"That's in the redacted section,\" she said.\n\n\"Which you have clearance for.\"\n\n\"Which I have clearance for.\"\n\nShe did not open the folder.\n\nKain looked at her hands on the folder's cover. The specific quality of their stillness. The decision that stillness represented, made before he asked the question, possibly before she sat down.\n\nHe picked up the first Solis journal.\n\n\"I'll need copies of these,\" he said.\n\n\"I can arrange access to the official record,\" Emily said. \"The folders can be—\"\n\n\"These,\" he said. He set the journal down on the table between them, its spine facing her, the faded green cover and the handwritten dates and the clean inside front cover with its absent barcode and its absent manifest label all present and legible in the fluorescent light.\n\nEmily looked at the journal.\n\nTwo seconds. Three.\n\n\"I'll arrange it,\" she said.\n\nHe picked the journal back up and turned to page forty-three.\n\n*I have begun to count the number of times I am told something is for my protection.*\n\nOutside, the mountain held its granite silence. The proximity field pressed. The fluorescent light examined everything it touched. Kain read, and Emily sat across the table with her hands flat on the redacted folder, and the Gen-3 scanner pointed at the empty chair with its patient, indifferent attention, and the room continued to be exactly what it was.",
