          "text": "The peripheral fragmentation hit without warning — his left visual field dropping out for a full second, the eastern wall of the apartment simply absent, replaced by the specific non-colour of a visual cortex running without input. He stopped moving. Pressed two fingers to his carotid. Counted.\n\nEighty-eight. High.\n\nThe fragmentation passed. The eastern wall returned — the desk, the terminal, the lamp on the wrong side, all of it reassembling with the slightly-too-sharp quality that followed a Bleed episode, the visual cortex overcorrecting for the interruption.\n\nOne second. That was longer than the Fitzroy North episode four years ago, which had been half a second. Longer than the car park behind the Pearl two nights ago, which had been three-quarters.\n\nThe window was fourteen months at the median. He was not at the median's beginning.\n\nHe filed this and kept working.",
