          "text": "Reality B-734 smelled of copper and standing water.\n\nThat was the first thing — always the first thing, coming through. The baseline smelled of nothing in particular, the way air smelled when it had been breathed by enough people for long enough that it had become anonymous. B-734 smelled of the specific mineral sharpness of water that had sat in old pipes, and of the copper oxidation in the relay infrastructure that the QSA had never bothered to upgrade in this branch because B-734 was a monitoring node, not an operational one, and monitoring nodes received maintenance on a seventeen-year cycle.\n\nHayden had been using it as an insertion point for eight months.\n\nHe stood in the maintenance corridor behind the hospital's eastern substation and waited for his legs to work.\n\nThis was the second thing — always the second thing. The legs. The transition from B-734 to baseline required the body to recalibrate its proprioceptive model from scratch, because the gravitational constant in B-734 ran 0.3 percent heavier than baseline and the body, after even a short stay, had adjusted its muscle tension accordingly. Coming back meant the legs expected more resistance than the floor provided. For approximately ninety seconds after transition, the body moved through baseline as though the ground might give way.\n\nFour hundred and twelve transitions. He had ninety seconds of unreliable legs four hundred and twelve times.\n\nHe pressed his back against the corridor wall and counted his pulse. Not at the wrist — the radial pulse had become unreliable six months ago, the vessel walls thickening in a pattern that Winters had described, in her notes, as *coherence calcification*, the body's connective tissue attempting to stabilize itself against the repeated quantum state disruptions by depositing calcium in the arterial walls. He counted at the carotid instead. Ninety-one. High, but within the post-transition range. It would drop to seventy-eight within four minutes.\n\nThe ICS reading on his subdural monitor pulsed once — a single blue flash behind his left eye, the notification he had configured to replace the audio alert he'd disabled eight months ago when the audio alert had begun triggering the auditory fragmentation. The reading: *34*.\n\nThirty-four. Down from thirty-seven at his last check, six days ago.\n\nThe Identity Coherence Score measured the degree to which the body's quantum state remained internally consistent — the degree to which the cellular-level information that made a specific person a specific person held together across repeated transitions. A baseline human, never transitioned, scored between 95 and 100\\. The QSA's operational threshold for active field personnel was 70\\. Below 60, the agency's medical protocols required mandatory stand-down and coherence stabilization treatment.\n\nBelow 40, the protocols had a different name. Hayden had read them once, in a file he wasn't supposed to have access to, and had not read them again.\n\nThirty-four.\n\nHis legs steadied. He pushed off the wall.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe hospital's eastern service entrance used a standard QSA-adjacent security protocol — the same biometric lock architecture that the agency had licensed to civilian medical facilities under the 2149 Public Infrastructure (Quantum Security) Agreement. Hayden had the override codes. He had obtained them from the same source as everything else: a QSA internal archive that he had accessed during his third month of operation, when his ICS had still been at 61 and his hands had still been reliable and the transition headaches had lasted four hours instead of eleven.\n\nThe lock opened. He went in.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe service corridor ran the length of the eastern wing's ground floor, parallel to the public corridor but separated from it by a wall of reinforced concrete that the hospital's 2134 renovation had installed to meet the updated seismic standards. The lighting was motion-activated and came on in sections as he moved — a thirty-metre pool of fluorescent white, then darkness, then another pool as the next sensor triggered.\n\nJacob was at the junction.\n\nHe was doing his job. Standing at the intersection of the service corridor and the stairwell access, his back to the wall, his attention on the tablet in his left hand — the shift log, updated every thirty minutes, the kind of task that occupied the hands without occupying the mind. He was a large man, broad through the shoulders, with the particular physical confidence of someone who had spent years in a role that occasionally required it. His ID badge hung from a lanyard at chest height.\n\nHe looked up when the motion sensor triggered the next pool of light.\n\nHayden was already inside the sensor's range. He kept walking. His pace did not change.\n\nJacob's hand moved toward the radio at his hip. Standard protocol — unscheduled personnel in a restricted corridor, radio first, questions second.\n\nHayden closed the distance in four steps. His right hand found the specific point at the junction of Jacob's neck and shoulder — the brachial plexus, the nerve cluster that, under sufficient targeted pressure, produced immediate motor disruption in the arm and a pain response that overrode every other cognitive process for approximately two seconds. Two seconds was enough. His left hand controlled the radio before it cleared the holster. He took Jacob's weight as the man's legs went, guided him to the floor with the practiced efficiency of someone who had done this before and had learned, through repetition, that the difference between a controlled descent and an uncontrolled one was the difference between a guard who woke up with a headache and a guard who didn't wake up at all.\n\nJacob's head touched the floor. His breathing held — steady, unconscious, the slow rhythm of someone who had been removed from the situation rather than damaged by it.\n\nHayden took the radio. Took the tablet. Checked the shift log for the next scheduled check-in: forty-two minutes.\n\nHe left Jacob in the corridor and went up the stairs.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe neurology department occupied the third floor's eastern wing. At 2:20 AM it held two nurses at the central station, one resident in the on-call room at the corridor's far end, and the specific institutional silence of a ward where the patients were sedated and the staff had reached the point in the night shift where conversation required more energy than it returned.\n\nHayden moved through it the way he moved through everything — with the specific quality of someone who belonged in the space and had somewhere to be. Not hurrying. Not hesitating. The white coat he'd taken from the locker room on the ground floor was two sizes too large across the shoulders, but nobody looked at the fit of a coat at 2:20 AM.\n\nDr. Sarah Winters occupied office 3-14. Her name was on the door in the standard hospital font, below her title: *Consultant Neurologist, Quantum Adjacency Disorders Unit.*\n\nThe lock was a standard hospital keycard system — not QSA-adjacent, not biometric. He had the master override on a card he'd cloned from the facilities management system three weeks ago, during a reconnaissance transition he'd made specifically for this purpose.\n\nThe door opened. He went in. He closed it behind him.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe office held the accumulated disorder of someone who worked in it rather than performed in it. Files on the desk, physical and digital both. A whiteboard along the left wall covered in notation that was half medical shorthand and half something that looked, to Hayden's eye, like the early stages of a theoretical framework — the kind of notation that appeared when a researcher was working at the edge of what the existing vocabulary could describe and had begun inventing new symbols for the concepts that didn't have names yet.\n\nHe photographed the whiteboard first. Then the desk files.\n\nThen he opened her terminal.\n\nThe QSA's civilian medical data-sharing protocols gave Winters's unit access to the agency's anonymized PQ genotype database — the research cohort that the QSA maintained for the purpose of studying quantum adjacency disorders in the general population. Winters had been publishing from this database for six years. Her most recent paper, eighteen months ago, had described a treatment protocol for early-stage Bleed that had achieved a 34 percent reduction in fragmentation frequency in a cohort of twelve patients.\n\nHayden had read the paper four times.\n\nHe had read it because the treatment protocol described in section four — the coherence stabilization approach, the specific combination of targeted quantum field exposure and cellular-level calcium chelation — was the closest thing to a functional ICS recovery method that existed in the published literature. Not a cure. The paper was careful about that. Winters was careful about everything. But a stabilization. A slowing of the decline. A method that might, if applied to a subject whose ICS had not yet crossed the threshold below which the protocols had a different name, extend the operational window by a factor that the paper estimated, conservatively, at between eight and fourteen months.\n\nEight to fourteen months.\n\nHis ICS was thirty-four. The threshold was forty. He had crossed it six days ago, when the reading had dropped from forty-one to thirty-seven, and he had not told anyone because there was no one to tell and because telling someone would have required explaining what he was and what he had done and what the four hundred and twelve transitions had cost, and that was a conversation that ended in one of two ways and he had no interest in either.\n\nThe paper described twelve patients. The database held the anonymized records of all twelve. What the paper did not contain — what no published paper could contain, because the ethics protocols governing the QSA's civilian research database prohibited the inclusion of identifying information in any published work — was the treatment methodology in sufficient detail to replicate it without Winters's direct involvement.\n\nThat methodology was in her unpublished notes.\n\nHe found them in the third subdirectory of her research partition, behind a password that took him four minutes to break — not because it was sophisticated, but because his hands had developed, over the past three months, a tendency to miskey under pressure. The coherence calcification in the arterial walls had begun to affect the fine motor control in his fingers. He had adapted. He typed more slowly now, and checked each entry before confirming it, and had learned to treat the extra time as a cost of operation rather than a failure of execution.\n\nHe copied the directory to the encrypted drive. All of it — the notes, the raw data, the correspondence with the QSA's research liaison, the draft of the follow-up paper that Winters had not yet submitted and that contained, in its methodology section, the specific treatment parameters that the published version had omitted.\n\nThe copy took six minutes. He stood at the terminal and watched the progress bar and listened to the ward's 2:20 AM silence and counted his pulse at the carotid.\n\nSeventy-nine. Down from ninety-one. On schedule.\n\nThe ICS monitor pulsed once behind his left eye. He did not look at the reading.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nHe was back in the service corridor at 2:41 AM. Jacob was where he'd left him — breathing steady, position unchanged, the shift log tablet on the floor beside his right hand. Hayden set the radio down next to it. Jacob would wake in approximately twenty minutes with a headache concentrated in the left shoulder and neck and no clear memory of the preceding two minutes. He would file an incident report. The incident report would describe an unscheduled individual in the service corridor. The description would be accurate and useless.\n\nHayden went out through the service entrance and into the car park.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe transition point was the maintenance corridor behind the eastern substation. He had forty minutes before the B-734 insertion window closed — the coherence alignment between baseline and B-734 held for ninety minutes at this geographic location, and he had used fifty of them.\n\nHe stood in the corridor and prepared.\n\nPreparation was not a ritual. It was a medical procedure he performed on himself, without equipment, in the dark. He checked his pulse. Seventy-eight — baseline for post-transition recovery, which meant his body had stabilized from the inbound crossing and was now operating at its current normal, which was not the same as healthy but was the best available approximation. He flexed his fingers — all ten, in sequence, checking the fine motor response. The ring and little finger of his right hand lagged by approximately forty milliseconds. Consistent with the last six transitions. Not worsening.\n\nHe checked the ICS monitor. *Thirty Two*\n\nTwo points in forty minutes. The transition stress was accelerating the decline. He had known this was possible — Winters's notes described it, in the section on advanced-stage coherence degradation, as *transition-induced cascade*, the phenomenon by which the quantum state disruption of a crossing event destabilized the body's remaining coherence faster than the recovery period could compensate. Below a certain ICS threshold, each transition cost more than the interval between transitions could restore.\n\nHe was below that threshold. He had been below it for six days.\n\nHe initiated the transition.\n\nThe first thing was the sound — a frequency below hearing that the body registered as pressure rather than noise, a compression that began at the sternum and moved outward through the ribcage and into the arms and legs and finally into the skull, where it became, for approximately three seconds, the specific agony of every sinus cavity attempting to equalize against a pressure differential that had no physical source. He had learned, across four hundred and twelve crossings, not to fight it. Fighting it extended the three seconds. Accepting it did not shorten them, but it preserved the muscle control he needed for what came after.\n\nThe pressure peaked. His vision went — not dark, not white, but absent, the visual cortex temporarily decoupled from its input as the quantum state transfer moved through the neurological architecture. He counted. One. Two. Three.\n\nThe weight of the air changed.\n\nB-734's 0.3 percent gravitational excess hit his legs first — the familiar, unwelcome heaviness, the floor suddenly more present than it had been, the body's recalibration beginning its ninety-second process. His vision returned in sections, the peripheral field first, then the center, the maintenance corridor assembling itself around him in the copper-and-standing-water air of a branch reality that had been running parallel to baseline for longer than anyone currently alive had been alive.\n\nHe was through.  \nThe collapse was not a failure of muscle, but a betrayal of physics.  \nHis legs didn't simply give; they ceased to be part of his recognized geometry. One moment he was a cohesive entity; the next, his proprioceptive map dissolved into a screaming static that left him untethered from the floor. He hit the concrete with a wet, jarring thud that he felt in his teeth before he felt it in his knees. The transition-induced cascade was no longer a theoretical threat in a file; it was a physical predator. It felt like his marrow was being replaced with molten lead, a heavy, agonizing heat that pulsed in time with the jagged rhythm of his failing heart.  \nHe tried to push up, but his right hand didn't find the wall; it passed through a ghost of a wall, a sensory lag that left him clawing at empty, copper-tasting air. His vision fractured into a kaleidoscopic nightmare where the maintenance corridor competed with the strobe-light flicker of a dozen other realities he had touched and discarded. The sweet, sick smell of burnt ozone filled his lungs, choking him, as the ICS monitor behind his eye didn't just pulse—it burned, a branding iron of light that screamed the number **32** into his very consciousness.  \nThe psychological horror was the sudden, absolute certainty that the version of Hayden Marsh that had entered the corridor was gone, and whatever was currently twitching on the cold concrete was just a collection of residual habits and dying echoes. He wasn't just losing his balance; he was losing the 'I' that felt the loss. He gasped, the copper air of B-734 thick and suffocating, and for five seconds of pure, unadulterated panic, he couldn't remember his own name. He was just a terminal frequency, vibrating until it shattered.  \nBy sheer, visceral desperation, he hooked his fingers into a gap in the wall’s conduit. He dragged his weight upward, the friction of the brick against his palm the only thing proving he still occupied a material form. He forced his spine to lock against the vertical plane, his breath coming in ragged, sobbing hitches. He stood there, a broken instrument held together by spite and adrenaline, staring into the dark and waiting for the one hundred and seven beats of his heart to stop sounding like a countdown to his own erasure.\n\nThe encrypted drive was in his jacket pocket. Winters's notes. The treatment methodology. The specific parameters that the published paper had omitted and that represented, if they were what he believed them to be, the difference between thirty-two and something that was not thirty-two.\n\nHe had forty minutes before the B-734 monitoring cycle ran its passive scan. He needed to be out of the corridor and into the safe house before then.\n\nHis pulse: ninety-four.\n\nHe pushed off the wall and walked.",
