          "text": "The kitchen drawer beside the sink was the last thing.\n\nChen's passive optical record showed a consistent pattern across nine years: the drawer opened with the left hand, always, because it was positioned to the left of the sink and a left-handed man reaching for it while standing at the sink reached with his dominant hand. The drawer held the items Chen used most frequently at the sink — the dish brush, the small knife for cutting fruit, the cloth he used to wipe the counter.\n\nThe drawer's handle carried a wear pattern. Nine years of the same grip, the same angle of approach, the same pressure — the metal slightly more polished on the left side of the handle, where the thumb of a left hand had contacted it thousands of times.\n\nThe wear was on the left side of the handle.\n\nThe smudge on the handle — the most recent contact, still faintly present on the brushed metal surface — was on the right side.\n\nKain stood at the kitchen sink and looked at the drawer handle and thought about Martina Solis writing on page forty-three of her second journal: *The replacement does not know why it reaches for the coffee with the left hand. It simply does.*\n\nThe replacement in Chen's apartment had not reached for the drawer with the left hand. It had reached with the right. Because the residue — Chen's left-hand dominance — had not encoded the drawer. The drawer was too small. Too peripheral. The replacement had been given Chen's major habits, his professional patterns, his institutional memory. It had not been given the drawer.\n\nNobody had given it the drawer because nobody had thought the drawer mattered.\n\nKain photographed the handle. The compression mark on the desk. The shower dial. The spine crease in the *Maltese Falcon*. He logged each one against the passive optical record, timestamped, with a notation that cross-referenced the residue theory from Solis's journal.\n\nFour anomalies. Four instances of a right-handed person moving through a left-handed life and leaving the specific, invisible evidence of the mismatch in the places too small to memorize and too habitual to notice.\n\nThe QSA's instruments had missed all of them.\n\nHe stood at the kitchen window and looked at the river fourteen floors below — the Yarra running its brown, patient course through the city, indifferent to the apartment above it and the dead man who had lived in it and the thing that had lived in it after him.\n\nHis right hand was in his jacket pocket. The tremor ran its frequency. His left visual field held.\n\nHe had four anomalies and a methodology and fourteen months, median probability.\n\nHe took out his tablet and began writing the report.",
