          "text": "*SECTION 3 — THE BASELINE PROTOCOL AND OPERATIONAL HISTORY*\n\n*The QSA has deployed PQ carriers as convergence baselines for 61 years. Of 1,847 confirmed carriers in the registry, 412 have been operationally deployed.*\n\n*Operational deployment does not require the carrier's informed consent under CDIR-CONV-2618-03, Article 7, which designates PQ carrier status as a QSA-classified medical condition and the carrier's resonance data as QSA institutional property.*\n\n*The carrier is not a subject. The carrier is an instrument.*\n\n*The QSA's clinical data establishes the following median deployment thresholds:*\n\n*— 3 deployments: buffer efficiency 71%. Carrier asymptomatic.* *— 7 deployments: buffer efficiency 44%. Low-frequency Bleed onset.* *— 12 deployments: buffer efficiency 19%. High-frequency Bleed, proprioceptive disruption, measurable ICS volatility.* *— 14 deployments: buffer efficiency below 15% recovery threshold. Terminal degradation. Median time to ICS collapse: 4–7 months.*\n\nKain pressed the flat of his free hand against the wall.\n\nNot the bypass switch — the wall itself, the aggregate concrete, the specific cold of a surface that had been absorbing this building's air conditioning for decades and would continue doing so after he left. He pressed it and held it and let the texture anchor the somatosensory cortex against the thing the table had just described.\n\nSeven deployments when the fragmentation first presented. The file called that *low-frequency Bleed onset*. The fragmentation had been getting worse at a rate consistent with the distance between seven and wherever he currently was.\n\nHe counted. He arrived at eleven.\n\nTwelve was next.\n\nHe kept reading because the alternative was to stop.",
