          "chapterId": "93a2e767-5c92-45e2-9bb2-886e2392cbc8",
          "title": "Scene 1",
          "text": "Emily's call came at nine-fourteen.\n\nKain sat in the atrium, in the chair with the sightline to the elevator bank. A porter wheeled an empty gurney toward the service corridor with the particular unhurried efficiency of someone whose route had become muscular rather than cognitive. The atrium had filled in the twenty minutes since he had sat down — the morning's patient load arriving in the specific rhythm of a hospital that ran on appointment schedules, people moving through the space with the focused purposefulness of those who knew where they were going and the slower, more uncertain movement of those who did not.\n\nHe answered before the second ring.\n\n\"Winters badged in at seven fifty-two this morning,\" Emily said. No preamble. \"That's forty-three minutes earlier than her average arrival time across the last eleven years of entry logs. The standard deviation on her arrival time is six minutes. Forty-three minutes is seven standard deviations outside her mean.\"\n\n\"What's her earliest recorded arrival?\"\n\n\"Eight twenty-one. Three years ago. The day her research grant was approved.\"\n\nSeven standard deviations. The number was not a statistical anomaly. It was a signature — the specific kind of error a replacement made when it had absorbed the subject's external schedule but not the internal logic that governed it. Winters arrived when her work required her to arrive. The replacement had arrived when its operational timeline required it to arrive, and had not understood that those two things were different.\n\n\"The nine o'clock appointment,\" Kain said.\n\n\"Booked four days ago through the hospital's internal scheduling system using Winters's credentials. The patient name is redacted, but the appointment type is listed as a follow-up consultation.\" Emily paused. \"Winters doesn't do follow-up consultations. Her research clinic runs initial assessments and data collection. Follow-ups go to the clinical team.\"\n\n\"The replacement booked an appointment with its own network contact. Using Winters's system access to create a legitimate-looking meeting.\"\n\n\"That's the most probable interpretation.\"\n\n\"I need the floor plan for the second-floor research wing. Every exit, every camera position, every room that connects to the corridor outside the clinic.\"\n\n\"Sending now.\"\n\nThe floor plan arrived on his phone thirty seconds later — a clean architectural drawing annotated in Emily's hand with camera positions in red and exit routes in blue. He studied it for forty seconds, building the geometry of the space in his mind, mapping the replacement's most probable movement patterns against the available exits.\n\nThe replacement had arrived forty-three minutes early. The nine o'clock appointment had ended fourteen minutes ago. The replacement remained in the clinic, moved through the building, or had already vanished.\n\nHe stood and moved toward the elevator bank.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nPeople now occupied the second-floor corridor. A shift change had occurred sometime in the last twenty minutes — the nurses' station at the far end staffed by two people, the three closed doors on the left side of the corridor carrying the particular quality of spaces that were occupied rather than vacant. A cleaner moved a mop bucket along the far wall with the slow, methodical progress of someone working to a pattern rather than a deadline. A man in a visitor's lanyard stood outside the middle door with his arms crossed and his weight on his left foot, the posture of someone who had been waiting long enough to stop pretending he was comfortable with it.\n\nKain walked the corridor at the pace of someone who belonged there — not hurried, not casual, the specific tempo of a person with a destination and a reason for it. He passed the nurses' station without stopping, his attention on the appointment board. The nine o'clock slot showed a check mark beside the redacted patient name. The ten-thirty data review session was unchanged.\n\nThe nine o'clock appointment was complete. The replacement had been in this corridor within the last fourteen minutes.\n\nHe stopped at the window overlooking the internal courtyard and used his phone screen as a partial mirror to observe the corridor behind him without turning. The cleaner. The man with the visitor's lanyard. A nurse moving between the station and the far door. No one whose movement pattern carried the specific quality he was looking for.\n\nThe residue theory was not complicated in principle. A replacement absorbed the subject's external presentation — appearance, credentials, behavioral habits documented in observable records. What it could not absorb was the subject's relationship to physical space. The way a person moved through a familiar environment was the product of years of accumulated micro-decisions: which side of the corridor they favored, how they navigated around obstacles, the specific rhythm of their interaction with doors and equipment they had used hundreds of times. A replacement navigating Winters's environment for the first time moved through it with a fractional excess of attention — the attention of someone reading a space rather than inhabiting it.\n\nHe needed to find that excess.\n\nHe turned from the window and walked to the nurses' station.\n\nThe nurse behind the desk was in her mid-thirties, her attention split between a screen and a printed schedule she was annotating in pencil. She looked up when he reached the counter.\n\n\"I'm looking for Dr. Winters,\" he said. He produced the QSA field credential — not the full identification, which would trigger a reporting protocol, but the civilian liaison card that established him as a government health researcher. \"I had a nine o'clock with her. I think I may have the wrong floor.\"\n\nThe nurse's expression moved through three registers in under two seconds: mild irritation at the interruption, the professional recalibration that followed, and then something more careful. \"Dr. Winters's nine o'clock was in room two-fourteen. That's—\" She stopped. \"Can I ask what this is regarding?\"\n\n\"Cohort data review. She's been consulting on a neurological study we're running through the health department.\"\n\nThe nurse looked at the schedule in front of her, then at the screen. \"Dr. Winters checked out of the building at nine-twelve.\"\n\nNine-twelve. The appointment had ended at nine, or close to it. The replacement had been in the building for twelve minutes after the appointment concluded — long enough to remove the white coat, retrieve whatever it had come for, and execute the withdrawal.\n\n\"Did she say where she was going?\"\n\n\"She doesn't usually—\" The nurse stopped again. The careful expression returned, more pronounced this time. \"Is there something wrong?\"\n\n\"No,\" Kain said. \"I must have the time wrong. I'll reschedule.\"\n\nHe moved away from the station before she could ask another question.\n\nRoom two-fourteen was the second door on the left — the one with the locked keycard reader he had noted on his first pass through the corridor. He stopped outside it and looked at the door without touching it. The keycard reader's indicator light showed green. Someone had unlocked it recently and not re-engaged the lock on exit.\n\nHe pushed the door open.\n\nThe room was small — a consultation space, not a research lab. Two chairs facing each other across a low table, a desk against the far wall with a monitor and keyboard, a single window overlooking the internal courtyard. The desk surface was clear except for a pen and a printed form that had been placed face-down. He turned the form over.\n\nIt was a standard patient intake document, blank except for a name in the top field: \\*M. Reyes.\\* No date of birth, no contact information, no medical history. The name had been written in a hand that was careful rather than natural — the deliberate letter formation of someone copying a signature they had practiced rather than producing their own.\n\nHe photographed the form and left the room.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe staff corridor beyond the STAFF ONLY door was narrower, lower-ceilinged, the institutional green replaced with unpainted concrete. Service infrastructure ran along the upper walls — conduit, pipe, the bundled cabling of a building retrofitted with successive generations of technology without ever being fully rewired. The lighting was fluorescent and unshielded, tubes mounted directly to the ceiling without diffusers, producing a harsh, flat illumination that eliminated shadow and made the space feel simultaneously exposed and claustrophobic.\n\nThe elevator at the far end of the main corridor had opened while he was in room two-fourteen. He had not seen who stepped out. But the STAFF ONLY door showed the same tell as the keycard reader in two-fourteen — the mechanism not fully returned to its resting position, the door sitting a millimeter proud of the frame.\n\nSomeone had come through it in the last four minutes.\n\nHe pushed through into the staff corridor.\n\nA woman stood twenty meters ahead of him.\n\nShe wore a white coat over dark clothing, a hospital ID badge on a lanyard, and carried a tablet in her left hand. Her hair was dark, pulled back, and her age was consistent with the photograph in Winters's personnel file. She moved down the corridor at a pace that was correct — not hurried, not uncertain — her attention on the tablet in her hand.\n\nBut her left hand was wrong.\n\nThe tablet was in her left hand, and she scrolled with her right thumb, which meant the tablet was oriented with the screen facing away from her body. Winters was left-handed. The personnel file noted it in the medical history section — a minor detail, the kind that appeared in records because it was clinically relevant to certain neurological assessments. A left-handed person holding a tablet in their left hand would orient it with the screen facing their body, scrolling with their left thumb or their right index finger. The orientation the woman used was the orientation of a right-handed person who had been told to carry the tablet in their left hand.\n\nKain moved after her.\n\nShe turned left at the end of the corridor, through a door marked STAFF ONLY that she opened with a keycard without breaking stride. He reached the door four seconds after it closed and used his Level 4 clearance to follow her through.\n\nThe corridor beyond was narrower still — a service passage, the walls bare concrete, the floor a rubberized surface that absorbed footsteps. The woman was fifteen meters ahead. He maintained the distance, keeping her in his peripheral vision rather than his direct sightline, moving with the same unhurried tempo she used.\n\nShe stopped.\n\nNot the stop of someone who had reached a destination. The stop of someone who had registered a presence behind them and was deciding what to do about it. She stood with her back to him for three full seconds, the tablet still in her left hand, the screen still facing away from her body.\n\nThen she turned around.\n\nHer face was Winters's face — the same bone structure, the same coloring, the same arrangement of features that appeared in the personnel file photograph. But the expression was wrong. Winters's photograph showed a woman in her mid-forties with the particular quality of attention that came from years of research work — focused, slightly distracted, the expression of someone whose mind was always partially elsewhere. The expression on the face in front of him was different. It was the expression of someone running a rapid assessment of a situation and arriving at a conclusion.\n\n\"Can I help you?\" she said.\n\nThe voice was correct. The cadence was correct. The slight upward inflection at the end of the question was consistent with the audio recordings in Winters's public lecture archive.\n\n\"I think I'm turned around,\" Kain said. \"I'm looking for the research clinic.\"\n\n\"You're on the wrong floor.\" She pointed back the way he had come. \"Main corridor, elevator to two, turn left.\"\n\n\"Thank you.\"\n\nHe turned and walked back toward the door. Behind him, her footsteps resumed  — not in the direction she had been heading, but back the way she had come. The assessment had concluded. The withdrawal protocol had activated.\n\nHe went through the door and stopped on the other side of it, his back against the wall, and counted to five.\n\nThen he went back through.\n\nThe corridor was empty.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe Bleed arrived without warning at the corner where the service passage turned toward the fire exit stairwell.\n\nIt did not arrive as a gap this time. It arrived as an addition — a layer of sensory data superimposed over the concrete corridor with a completeness that made the corridor itself seem like the intrusion. The baseline room. The room from the Sphere's calibration sequence, with its too-white walls and the specific quality of ozone that the entanglement field generated as a byproduct of the magnetic levitation system. The smell arrived first — sharp, chemical, the smell of air ionized by eleven megawatts of continuous electromagnetic output. Then the walls, pressing in from the periphery of his visual field, white over concrete, the two surfaces occupying the same space with equal insistence.\n\nHe stopped walking.\n\nThe concrete, conduit, and fluorescent tubes remained. The building's ventilation system hummed somewhere below the floor. But the baseline room existed with equal force, its ozone smell overriding the concrete dust and recycled air of the service passage, its white walls asserting themselves against the grey of the unpainted surface in front of him. The two environments did not alternate. They coexisted, each one fully present, each one demanding the full processing capacity of a nervous system that could not divide itself between them without losing coherence in both.\n\nHe pressed his right hand flat against 