an sixty seconds in the stairwell. The replacement had known the exit route before it entered the building.\n\nKain moved through the loading dock and into the service lane.\n\nCommercial Road at nine-thirty on a Tuesday morning carried the specific density of a major arterial in a medical precinct — delivery vehicles, taxis, the slow accumulation of traffic around a hospital that drew its own sustained current of human movement. The footpath held the particular mix of people that gathered around large medical facilities: staff on breaks, visitors arriving and departing, the occasional patient moving with the careful deliberateness of someone recently discharged.\n\nThe woman was forty meters ahead, moving south at a pace that had changed. The correct, unhurried tempo of the corridor was gone. She moved now with the specific efficiency of someone executing a planned withdrawal — not running, not drawing attention, but covering ground at the maximum rate that did not constitute flight.\n\nHe followed.\n\nThe gap closed to thirty meters. Twenty-five. The footpath narrowed at a construction hoarding that extended from a building site across half the pedestrian space, compressing foot traffic into a single-file channel between the hoarding and the road. She entered the channel. He was ten seconds behind her.\n\nThe Bleed returned in the channel.\n\nThis time it was the laughing woman, and this time she was not behind his eyes. She occupied the space two meters ahead of him in the channel, her presence directional, located, as physically specific as the hoarding to his left and the road to his right. She laughed for four seconds — high, uncontrolled, the laugh of someone who had found something genuinely funny in a situation that contained nothing funny — and the sound had a position in space, a source point, as though she stood in the channel and was laughing at something she could see that he could not.\n\nHe stopped moving. The person behind him walked into his back a