w long did you have eyes on it?\"\n\n\"Six minutes. Maybe seven.\"\n\n\"Did you get a visual?\"\n\n\"Partial. Not enough.\" He started walking north, back toward the hospital. \"The intake form in room two-fourteen has a name. M. Reyes. Run it against the QSA civilian contact registry and the Alfred patient database.\"\n\n\"That'll take twenty minutes.\"\n\n\"I'll be inside.\" He paused. \"The ten-thirty data review session is still on the board. The replacement booked it. It may come back to complete it.\"\n\nSilence on Emily's end. Not the silence of processing — the silence of someone deciding whether to say the thing they were about to say. \"You think it'll return to a location it just fled.\"\n\n\"I think it has a network contact named Reyes and an unfinished data review session and a replacement protocol that requires both of those things to be completed before it moves to the next phase. Abandoning the session creates a gap in Winters's record that flags the breach. It won't want that gap.\"\n\n\"You're betting on its operational discipline.\"\n\n\"I'm betting on its instructions. There's a difference.\"\n\nHe ended the call and pushed back through the loading dock door.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe atrium at ten-fifteen held a different population than the one at nine o'clock. The morning's appointment rush had passed through and dispersed into the building's upper floors, leaving behind the slower, more settled density of people who were waiting rather than arriving. The family near the information desk had rearranged themselves — the sleeping child now awake and eating something from a paper bag, the adults in the same configuration but with the particular quality of people who had stopped pretending the wait had a predictable end.\n\nKain took a different chair this time — one with a sightline to both the elevator bank and the main entrance, positioned behind a structural column that broke his silhouette without obstructing his view. He had twelve minutes before the ten-thirty session. He used four of them to review the photograph of the intake form on his phone, studying the handwriting in the name field. The letters were formed with the careful deliberateness of someone who had practiced the motion rather than developed it — the \\*R\\* in Reyes slightly too upright, the \\*y\\* descending at an angle that was geometrically correct but not natural.\n\nThe replacement had written the name. Not Winters. The replacement had created a patient record for its own network contact using a name it had been given rather than one it had generated, and it had written that name in a hand that was not Winters's hand because it had not yet had enough time in the building to absorb the fine motor residue of Winters's writing.\n\nHis phone buzzed. Emily.\n\n\"M. Reyes doesn't appear in the QSA civilian contact registry,\" she said. \"The Alfred patient database has a Marcus Reyes, sixty-three, cardiac patient, last appointment fourteen months ago. No connection to the neurology research clinic.\"\n\n\"It's a cover name. The contact came in as a patient, used the intake form to pass something to the replacement, and left before the appointment officially ended.\"\n\n\"What did they pass?\"\n\n\"I don't know yet.\" He kept his eyes on the elevator bank. \"The data review session at ten-thirty. Is it still showing in the system?\"\n\nThe pause lasted three seconds. \"Yes. It's still active.\"\n\n\"Then the replacement is coming back.\"\n\nAt ten twenty-two, the elevator doors opened.\n\nThe woman who stepped out wore different clothing — dark trousers, a grey jacket, no white coat, no ID badge. Her hair was still pulled back. She carried nothing in either hand. She moved through the atrium toward the corridor that led to the research wing with the same correct, unhurried tempo she had used in the staff corridor, and her left hand swung at her side with the natural looseness of someone who was not carrying a tablet and had not yet remembered 