          "text": "The intake station occupied the last twenty metres of the Threshold facility's exit corridor — a narrowing of the passage that was architectural rather than accidental, designed to ensure that nothing left the building without passing through the sensor array embedded in the walls on both sides. The array was passive. It did not ask. It read.\n\nThe technician behind the desk was a woman in her thirties with the specific economy of movement that belonged to people who performed the same precise actions many times a day and had eliminated everything unnecessary. She did not look up when Kain approached. She held out her right hand, palm up, without breaking her attention from the terminal in front of her.\n\nHe placed his wrist against the scanner she held. The device was warm from continuous use. It ran its read in four seconds — the standard biometric sweep, pulse and temperature and the subcutaneous markers that the QSA used to track personnel movement through secured facilities.\n\nAnd then the PQ genotype flag. He knew the moment it hit because the technician's eyes moved — not to him, not to the terminal, but to a point approximately thirty centimetres to the left of both, the specific unfocused gaze of someone processing information they had not expected and were now deciding what to do with.\n\nOne second. Two.\n\nShe withdrew the scanner. Her eyes returned to the terminal. Her fingers moved across the input surface with the same precise economy as before, logging the exit, completing the record.\n\n\"Clear,\" she said.\n\nHe walked through.\n\nThe corridor beyond the intake station ran twelve metres to the facility's outer door. He walked it at the same pace he had walked every other corridor in the building — not slow, not fast, the pace of someone with somewhere to be and no reason to hurry. His right hand was in his jacket pocket, thumb against the seam. The tremor ran its low, reliable frequency.\n\nBehind him, the technician's termina