          "text": "The housing was a cylinder of poured concrete and electromagnetic shielding, twelve metres in diameter, sunk four floors below the Alfred's original foundation. Kain had the schematic in his left hand — not the digital version, the paper one, folded into quarters and already damp from the sweat of his palm — and he was not looking at it. He knew the schematic. He had memorised the schematic in the courier vehicle while the burner phone cycled through its third encryption relay. What he was looking at was the door.\n\nIt was open.\n\nHayden was already inside.\n\nHe checked his watch. The display read 14:07:22. He had established the SEP-NULL threshold at 14:07:00. He had twenty-two seconds of buffer remaining before the field's coherence degraded past the point of correction. He had 294 coordinates to verify and 54 wire corrections in his kit.\n\nThe arithmetic had been broken since Chapter 15\\. He had not fixed it. He had simply decided to enter the room anyway, because the alternative was standing in the corridor while the threshold collapsed and Hayden completed the map without him, and that outcome was not acceptable.\n\nHe went through the door.  \n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe Sphere's housing smelled of ozone and hot metal and something underneath both of those — a biological smell, faintly sweet, the specific olfactory signature of biophotonic decay that Emily had described in her third report and that Kain had not believed until he smelled it himself in the stairwell forty minutes ago. It was stronger here. It was much stronger here. The air tasted of it.\n\nThe Sphere itself occupied the centre of the room: a lattice of copper wire and ceramic insulators suspended inside a geodesic frame, the whole assembly roughly the size of a transit van stood on its end. The wire ran in 847 discrete loops, each loop corresponding to a coordinate in the QSA map, each coordinate representing a dimensional variance point where the baseline reality's coherence was w