she was not looking at him, which was why she had the red pen in her hand and was marking something in the file that did not need marking, which was why the coffee was still hot and the afternoon light was still perfect and the draught from the broken latch was still coming through the window, because this place was not a place, it was a proposition, and the proposition was: \\*stay, and all of this is yours, and none of it is real.\\*\n\nHe turned away from the table.\n\n\\*\\*\\*  \nThe housing came back in pieces.\n\nFirst the smell — ozone, hot metal, the sweet biological decay. Then the cold. Then the tremor in his left hand, returning like a tide, the fine oscillation resuming exactly where it had stopped, as though the Bleed had simply paused it rather than ended it. Then the pressure behind his eyes, the grinding baseline, the tinnitus of a nervous system consuming itself.\n\nThen the wire in his hands, and the Sphere in front of him, and Hayden's frequency still arriving in black flashes, and the numbers still coming.\n\nHe had lost — he checked — four seconds. Four seconds of objective time inside a subjective experience that had felt like ten minutes in a warm kitchen with a solved case and a dead woman who was not dead in Reality B-734, only transferred, only gone in the specific way that meant she was somewhere else and not nowhere.\n\nHe had 54 wire corrections. He had used 12\\.\n\nHe had, now, four seconds of buffer remaining.\n\nThe math was still broken.\n\n\\*\\*\\*  \n629\\\\. 644\\. 671\\.\n\nHis hands moved. The tremor was worse — the four-second Bleed had cost him something in the buffer efficiency, the 19% reserve that Emily had calculated as his operational ceiling now clearly below that, the degradation accelerating in the way that terminal processes accelerate when they approach their conclusion. His left hand was producing errors. He could feel them: the wire seating a half-millimetre off-centre, the correction technically made but imprecisely, the coordinate verified but not cleanly.\n\nHe corrected for the errors by slowing down, which cost time he did not have.\n\nThe frequency from Hayden was changing. The blue-white density in the air around the Sphere's base was thinning — not because the frequency was weakening but because it was concentrating, pulling inward, the biophotonic output that had been bleeding into the building's steel for six hours now drawing back toward its source the way a tide draws back before it disappears entirely. Hayden's hands were still moving in the wire. His body was still present. But the quality of his presence was changing, the specific solidity of him becoming something more like the quality of the air around him — dense, charged, and not quite material.\n\nKain did not look at him. He looked at the wire.\n\n714\\\\. 731\\. 748\\.  \nTwo seconds.  \n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe second Bleed hit differently.\n\nNo transition. No kitchen. No warmth. Instead: a superimposition, both realities simultaneously present, the housing and the Punt Road flat occupying the same space, the Sphere's lattice visible through the kitchen table, the kitchen table visible through the Sphere's lattice, Solis sitting in a chair that was also the Sphere's base, the wire running through her hands, the coffee mug sitting on a ceramic insulator, the afternoon light and the fluorescent housing light both present and neither dominant.\n\nHis visual cortex tried to resolve the superimposition and failed. The failure registered as a white spike of pain behind his left eye, a specific, surgical agony that was not the grinding baseline but something acute and new, the kind of pain that meant a threshold had been crossed and a system had begun its shutdown sequence.\n\nHe closed his left eye.\n\nWith his right eye, he could isolate the housing. The Sphere. The wire. The coordinates.\n\nHe kept his left eye closed and kept working.\n\n765\\\\. 782\\. 799\\.\n\nOne second.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe buffer hit zero.\n\nHe felt it as a physical event: a sudden absence of resistance, the electromagnetic shielding that had been holding the SEP-NULL threshold in place simply ceasing to function, the field collapsing inward, and with it the last structural barrier between baseline reality and Reality B-734. The superimposition became total. Both realities were now fully present, fully coherent, fully competing for the same physical space, and his nervous system — already operating at the absolute limit of its degraded capacity — was now required to process both simultaneously.\n\nHis left hand stopped working.\n\nThe hand simply stopped receiving signals — there was only cessation without warning.  He looked at it: the fingers were curled around a length of wire, the grip maintained by the last instruction his motor cortex had successfully transmitted before the buffer collapse interrupted the pathway. He could not open the hand. He could not move the fingers. The hand was present and warm and completely non-functional.\n\nHe transferred the wire to his right hand.\n\n816\\\\. 831\\. 844\\.\n\nThree coordinates remaining.\n\nHayden's frequency arrived one final time — not as numbers, not as language, but as a single sustained note that Kain's auditory cortex translated as a frequency he recognised from Emily's third report: 7.83 Hz, the Schumann resonance, the electromagnetic frequency of the Earth's own baseline, the frequency that the biophotonic architecture had been mimicking for thirty-one years as it waited for a host system capable of reading it.\n\nThe note held for two seconds.\n\nThen it began to diminish.\n\n845\\\\.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe Sphere's lattice was changing. The copper wire in the sections he had corrected was no longer copper-coloured — it had taken on the blue-white quality of Hayden's frequency, the corrections he had made becoming part of the map rather than corrections to it, the 54 wire adjustments integrating into the lattice's geometry and altering the whole structure's resonance. He could see it propagating through the uncorrected sections, the frequency travelling the wire the way current travels a circuit, reaching coordinates he had not physically touched and correcting them through the map's own internal logic.\n\nThe math resolved itself.\n\nNot a miracle. A mechanism: the biophotonic frequency, concentrated now to its maximum output in the final seconds of its source's coherence, was completing the corrections that Kain's hands could not. Hayden's architecture, thirty-one years of accumulated dimensional data stored in a nervous system that had made 417 unauthorised jumps and survived all of them, was discharging into the map in a single sustained pulse, filling the 240-coordinate deficit that 54 wire corrections could never have covered.\n\nThe ghost in the machine was spending itself.\n\n846\\\\.\n\nKain's right hand found the final wire. His fingers were not steady — the tremor had migrated from his left hand to his right in the last thirty seconds, the degradation no longer confined to one pathway, the shutdown sequence generalising. He seated the wire. He felt the connection make. He felt the frequency travel through the correction and into the lattice and complete the circuit.\n\n847\\\\.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe superimposition ended.\n\nNot gradually. The Punt Road kitchen did not fade. It simply ceased to be present, the way a sound ceases when its source stops — not a diminuendo but an absence, immediate and total. The afternoon light was gone. The coffee was gone. Solis was gone. The housing was the housing: concrete and electromagnetic shielding and fluorescent light and the smell of ozone and the Sphere's lattice now fully integrated, all 847 coordinates verified, the map closed.\n\nThe blue-white density in the air around the Sphere's base was gone.\n\nHayden was gone.\n\nNot collapsed, not fallen — gone, in the specific way that a frequency is gone when the last of its energy has been discharged, when the source has given everything it had to give and there is nothing remaining to sustain the pattern. The space where he had been standing was slightly warmer than the surrounding air. That was all.\n\nKain stood in front of the closed map with his right hand still on the final wire and his left hand still curled around the wire it had gripped when the motor pathway failed, and he waited.\n\nThe map held.\n\nThe field did not collapse. The SEP-NULL threshold, which should have failed at the zero-second mark, was instead stabilising — the 847-coordinate closure providing the structural coherence that the electromagnetic shielding alone could not have maintained. The Bleed was not present. Reality B-734 was not present. The housing was the housing, and the air smelled of ozone, and his left hand did not work, and his right hand was trembling, and the pain behind his left eye was the specific pain of a threshold that had been crossed and would not be uncrossed.\n\nHe released the wire.\n\nHe took the lighter from his pocket.\n\nHe rolled the wheel.\n\nThe dry rasp of metal on spent flint. The faint chemical ghost of fuel nine years evaporated. No spark. No catch. No flame.\n\nHe put it back.\n\n\\*\\*\\*  \nHe found the door by memory — his visual field was compromised, the left eye still closed, the right eye producing a slight chromatic aberration at the periphery that he catalogued as a symptom and set aside. The corridor was empty. The ozone smell was present but diminishing, the field's stabilisation reducing the paradox residue that had been accumulating in the building's infrastructure for six hours.\n\nHe had the schematic in his right hand. He did not need it.\n\nHe walked.\n\nThe stairwell was four doors down. He counted the doors by touch, his right hand trailing the wall, the left arm hanging at his side with the hand still curled in its last transmitted position. At the stairwell door he stopped and assessed: four floors to the surface, one functional hand, a visual field operating at approximately 60% of baseline, a nervous system that had just processed a Level 5 Convergence event and a full SEP-NULL buffer collapse and was now running on whatever reserve capacity remained below the 19% threshold that Emily had identified as the operational floor.\n\nHe did not know what was below the floor. He was about to find out.\n\nHe opened the stairwell door and began to climb.\n\nThe first landing was concrete and fluorescent light and the smell of the building's ordinary infrastructure — cleaning products, recycled air, the specific institutional smell of a hospital's sub-basement. No overlay. No superimposition. The baseline held.\n\nSecond landing. Third.\n\nHis right hand found the railing and held it. His legs were functional. The tremor in his right hand was worsening — he could feel the railing vibrating under his grip, which was his hand and not the railing — but the legs were functional and the stairwell was the stairwell and the baseline held.\n\nFourth landing. The surface door.\n\nHe pushed through it into the hospital's ground-floor corridor, into the fluorescent light and the antiseptic smell and the specific ambient noise of a building full of people who did not know what had happened four floors below them, and he stood in the corridor for a moment with his back against the door and his right hand still on the handle and his left hand still curled and his left eye still closed.\n\nA nurse passed him without stopping. A porter with a linen cart. An orderly checking a tablet.\n\nThe baseline held.\n\nHe straightened. He opened his left eye. The chromatic aberration was still present at the periphery — a thin iridescent fringe at the edge of his visual field, the specific optical signature of a PQ pathway that had been pushed past its structural limit and would not fully recover. He catalogued it. He set it aside.\n\nHe began walking toward the exit.\n\nThe lighter was in his pocket. Dead. Broken. Non-functional.\n\nThe map was closed.\n\nThe case was not solved — cases were never solved, they were only closed, and the distinction mattered — but the map was closed, and the field was stable, and the Bleed was not present, and Hayden was gone in the way that a frequency is gone, which was not the same as dead, which was not the same as anything he had a word for yet.\n\nHe would find a word later.\n\nHe pushed through the exit door into the cold Melbourne air, into the specific grey of a late afternoon in a city that did not know it had just been held in its own baseline by a broken lighter and 54 wire corrections and the last discharge of a thirty-one-year-old biophotonic battery, and he stood on the pavement outside the Alfred Hospital and breathed the cold air and waited for his right hand to stop trembling.\n\nIt did not stop.\n\nHe put it in his pocket, next to the lighter, and walked.",
