          "text": "She closed the file.\n\nShe sat for a moment with her hands flat on the table — both of them now, symmetrical, the way she positioned herself before a job when she needed her nervous system to understand that the planning phase was over and execution had begun.\n\nThe receipt was on the kitchen bench. She'd found it in his jacket pocket six weeks ago when she'd been looking for the building access card he'd misplaced — which was itself a symptom she'd filed under *fatigue* before she had a better category for it. A pharmacy receipt, not their usual procurement channel, itemised with a generic brand she'd had to look up. Prophylactic neuroinhibitors, daily dosing, three-month supply. She'd photographed it and replaced it and said nothing, because the shape of the thing was not yet fully known.\n\nThe shape of the thing was now fully known.\n\nShe stood, went to the kitchen, picked up the receipt, and placed it in the partition file along with everything else she had collected. Timestamps, the pharmacy receipt, the ICS trajectory she had now reconstructed across 417 data points. The file was thorough. It was the kind of file a person built when they understood, on some level, that they were going to need it to be thorough.\n\nShe did not call Emily.\n\nShe had thought, in the abstract, that Emily would be the correct person to contact. Emily had resources, institutional reach, the ability to pull Hayden off the field before jump 418\\. She had also, at some point in the last four years, approved the operational parameters that allowed a man with an ICS of 41 to continue active fieldwork without mandatory disclosure to his partner. Bell had no direct evidence of that. She had sufficient inference. The QSA did not run operations like this without authorisation at the handling level, and Emily was the handler, and the handler knew the asset's status or the handler was negligent, and Emily was not negligent.\n\nShe did not call Kain. She did not know Kain. She knew his name from Hayden's early-cycle logs — the QSA Norm consultant, the dormant carrier Emily had brought in as a procedural instrument. She knew Kain the way she knew other moving parts in an operation she hadn't planned: as a variable to account for, not to contact. Whatever Kain was walking into in next, he would walk into it without knowing the anchor variable was already in motion. That was not her problem to solve. She had one operation running now, and it required her complete attention.\n\nShe went to the bathroom. Ran cold water. Looked at her own hands under the tap — both of them steady, which was information. Her nervous system had already accepted the transition from *planning* to *execution* and was running accordingly. She turned the tap off.\n\nIn the bedroom, Hayden moved — chair scraping slightly, the particular rhythm of someone shifting weight without standing up. She knew the acoustics of the apartment the way she knew the acoustics of every space she'd worked in for more than a month. She knew his weight distribution on the desk chair versus the floor. She knew the difference between the scrape that meant he was stretching and the scrape that meant he was standing, and this was the first one, which meant she had time.\n\nShe went back to the main room.\n\nShe pulled up the secondary comm device and navigated to the Docklands extraction route file — the original, not the laminated copy on the board. She annotated it with the timestamp of tonight's check-in, added it to the partition file, and closed the partition.\n\nThen she unpinned the laminated route from the ops board.\n\nShe stood with it for a moment. His handwriting in the upper quadrant. The *just in case* corridor. The red marker annotations that had saved the Docklands job and that she had looked at every day for six weeks while building a file that now explained exactly what kind of instrument she had been to the man who made them. She rolled the laminate carefully — she was always careful with physical materials, this had not changed and would not change — and placed it in the flat sleeve she used for documents that needed to travel without damage.\n\nShe put the sleeve in her go-bag.\n\nShe did not take anything else that night. That was the point. One item, chosen for operational relevance, removed without altering the visual register of the room. She had thirty-one minutes of declared network maintenance remaining. She used nine of them.\n\nWhen Hayden came out of the bedroom thirty-five minutes later and found her at the comm board running what looked like standard legacy contact management, she had already decided on the sequence. Not when. She hadn't decided when. She had decided the geometry: incremental, untriggered, each removal calibrated below the threshold of his residue-reading. The go-bag had always been partially packed. The sleeve had always been a document sleeve in a bag that had always contained document sleeves. The ops board had gaps from prior safe houses going dark. One more gap read as operational maintenance.\n\nShe understood residue-reading because he had taught her. He had sat across from her in the early months — the Fitzroy safe house, the draughty windows, the coffee going cold — and explained how a replacement betrayed itself. Not through facts, but through the absence of the psychological logic behind facts. The *why* of a person's habits. He had said: *the human animal leaves a pattern in a room, and the pattern is not the furniture, it's the friction between the furniture and the person's body. You learn to read the friction.*\n\nShe had learned to read the friction.\n\nHe had been teaching her a skill that was also, in some sense, a confession of method. That the man who could read the friction of a stranger's apartment had spent four years producing, for her benefit, a perfectly calibrated friction. The right habits in the right register. The red annotations. The *just in case* corridor. The thirty-second check-in delivered in the same tone whether the preceding fourteen minutes had been routine network maintenance or the discovery that she was a pharmacological instrument with a documented replacement cost of twenty-three percent.\n\nTwenty-three percent.\n\nThat was what she was worth, expressed in the language he used when he thought no one was reading.\n\nShe said nothing. She ran her legacy contact maintenance. She went to bed when he went to bed. She lay in the dark and listened to him breathe — the slightly irregular rhythm that had developed around jump 300, the one she'd filed under *fatigue* and then under *nerve compression* and then under the growing category of things she had accepted his explanation for because she had been paying attention to everything except the right thing. The rhythm was present-tense. It was the breathing of a man still running, still operational, still convinced the window was sufficient. Still convinced she didn't know.\n\nShe was very still and very awake until well past three in the morning.\n\nBy then she had the geometry fully mapped.\n\nShe would leave in increments small enough that he would not clock the decay until she was already gone. Not for his sake. For hers — because a clean exit was a professional exit, and she was, regardless of what the last four years had been in his clinical shorthand, a professional. She would not slam a door. She would not create a confrontation that gave him information about the timeline of her departure. She would remove herself from the equation the same way she removed herself from any compromised operational environment: quietly, completely, and without leaving a retrievable pattern.\n\nAnd because if he knew she was leaving before she was gone, he would still have the window. Twenty-three percent. Thirty-five jumps.\n\nShe was not willing to be the thing that gave him those jumps.\n\nShe closed her eyes. She did not sleep for a long time.\n\nIn the morning she made coffee — black, the way she'd always made it, the way he had presumably documented that she made it in a log entry she hadn't reached before the check-in cut her window short. She would read the remaining entries later, in the partition file, on the secondary device, somewhere he was not.\n\nShe handed him a cup. He said *thanks* in the distracted register of someone already inside their operational thinking, his attention on the terminal and not on her, which was operationally convenient and not, at this point, anything else. She said nothing.\n\nHis left hand tremored slightly around the mug. He clamped it with his right without looking at it. The correction was smooth and practiced — a compensation so thoroughly integrated into his physical routine that it no longer registered as a correction, just as a way of holding a cup. It was entirely invisible unless you had been watching it for six weeks and knew exactly what you were seeing and had now read, in his own clinical shorthand, the entry where he had first documented it and decided not to tell her.\n\nShe looked at her own coffee.\n\nOutside, Melbourne ran its morning traffic through the gap between the warehouse roller door and the sill — trams, early freight, the particular acoustic texture of a city resuming itself after rain. She had been here long enough to know this sound the way she knew his breathing. Long enough that leaving would mean re-learning a different city's acoustics from scratch, in a safe house that didn't have his chair scrape or his three-AM breathing or the slight drag of his right boot heel on the concrete floor that she had clocked on day four and filed under *gait* and never thought about again.\n\nShe drank her coffee.\n\nShe did not look at the ops board, where the laminated route was no longer pinned.\n\nHe hadn't noticed yet.",
