          "text": "Forty seconds. The physical collapse started in his left leg. Not a tremor, but a loss of tone—the muscle fiber relaxing its grip on the bone, the limb threatening to buckle beneath his weight. He shifted his weight, compensating with the right leg, a movement so precise and rapid that the passenger beside him did not register it as a failure. He had practiced this compensation for four years. The Bleed was now attacking the architecture he had constructed for survival.\n\nFifty seconds. He closed his eyes, cutting off the visual input, forcing the internal chaos to resolve itself in the auditory field. The sound of the tram was a violent, multi-directional screech, the noise of two separate vehicles traveling on the same track at incompatible speeds. He focused on his own pulse: fast, irregular, a frantic drumming against the cold metal. The pulse was the ultimate anchor. The pulse was the clock.\n\nSixty seconds. The fenugreek scent receded, replaced by the faint, miserable smell of old coffee in the tram’s floor. The white heat behind his eye began to dim, withdrawing to a dull, localized throbbing. The neurological static slowed to a manageable hum.\n\nSixty-one seconds.\n\nHe opened his eyes. The tram was still in Fitzroy, the architecture outside the window solid, specific, and real. The passenger was still looking at him, a flicker of concern in their expression. Kain nodded, a small, controlled gesture of acknowledgment that meant I am fine, move on. The passenger looked away.\n\nThe face was still gone. The specifics of the conversation were gone. He knew, abstractly, that the man on the tram was his own replacement, a terminal agent with a message. He knew the conversation had contained three pieces of data: a link, a designation, and a confrontation with Emily.\n\nBut the final piece of the conversation, the specific information about Voss and the operational designation that linked her to the Reyes alias—that was gone. The Bleed had erased it entirely, taking the highest-value data and leaving only the visceral, physical certainty of the attack.\n\nHe leaned his forehead against the cold metal of the door. The contact was solid, cold, real. He ran the inventory again, checking the internal systems against the physical clock. Sixty-one seconds. The longest collapse to date. The first one to leave a permanent hole in his working memory.\n\nThe tram slowed for the stop at Victoria Parade.\n\nThe memory was lost, but the instruction remained. The target was Emily. The confrontation was now immediate.\n\nHe pushed off the door and moved toward the frontof the carriage. He needed a secure line, a clean room, and twenty minutes to run the audit before she could flag his presence in the city and shut down the operation entirely.   \n\\*\\*\\*   \nThe folded paper was still on the seat. The Pelco unit was still logging. His phone was vibrating in his jacket pocket with the particular rhythm of Emily's direct line — not a message, a call, which meant the flag had arrived and she had not waited for the audio analysis.\n\nSix minutes had been optimistic.\n\nHe let it ring.\n\nHe had six stops before the terminus. Six stops in which the Pelco array would log his position, his stillness, his failure to retrieve an object that the behavioural software would eventually flag as a deliberate leave-behind or an operational drop, depending on which analyst was running the morning's review. He had six stops in which Emily's call would go to voicemail and she would decide what that meant. He had six stops in which the QSA's cross-reference engine would finish its work on the Nicholson Street boarding data and produce a report that would sit in Emily's queue alongside the proximity flag and the unanswered call, and the three data points together would form a picture that Emily was already capable of reading.\n\nShe had been capable of reading it for fourteen months.\n\nThe tram slowed for the next stop.\n\nKain reached across the aisle and picked up the folded paper.\n\nThe Pelco unit logged the movement. The behavioural software assigned it a score. The score would be in Emily's queue in ninety seconds, appended to everything else, and the picture would be complete, and she would know that he had it, and she would know that he had chosen to take it rather than leave it, which was the same as telling her that the conversation on the tram had happened and that he had listened and that he had not immediately reported it.\n\nHe put the paper in his jacket pocket without unfolding it.\n\nThe tram moved.\n\nHis phone stopped vibrating.\n\nIn thirty seconds it would start again.",
