          "chapterId": "c5c39ce4-a327-4989-bc06-6499b9b9269c",
          "title": "Scene 1",
          "text": "The first time Bell saw the failure, it was not in the field, where failures were loud and final. It was in the kitchen of the safe house, two weeks after the Alfred Hospital extraction, over a cup of black coffee that had gone cold.\n\nHayden was running a cross-reference on the Winters database query, his left hand braced against the edge of the counter, his right index finger tracking the data flow on the terminal with the speed and precision that she had once watched with detached professional admiration. He moved the cursor from a timeline to a geographical vector—a shift that required micro-musculature control—and the cursor twitched. Not a smooth, lateral move, but a small, involuntary jump, two pixels down and three to the left, before he corrected it.\n\nIt was negligible. The error was within the operating tolerance of a fatigued operator on a legacy terminal. He corrected it without comment, his gaze steady on the screen.\n\nBell’s hand was already moving. She did not reach for the tablet, did not make a sound. She reached for the kitchen clock and adjusted its digital time forward by forty-five seconds—an action so mundane and unnecessary that Hayden didn't look up, his attention locked on the data stream. She watched his neck, the line of his jaw. The correction of the cursor error had cost him a faint tightening of the masseter muscle, the same way a person tightens their jaw against the start of a deep, localized pain.\n\nShe filed the observation under a new category: ICS-Anomaly.\n\nShe walked around the counter, picked up her empty mug, and ran it under the tap, using the sound of the water to cover the two specific, purposeful movements she executed next. The first was to stop at the fridge, where she had clipped a laminated copy of their shared Fitzroy safe house floor plan to the magnetic surface. The second was to use the phone in her pocket—the secondary, compartmentalized device—to photograph the laminated plan.\n\nShe took the photograph not of the entire plan, but of a small, specific section: the corridor geometry between the main living area and the bedroom.\n\nWhen she got back to the counter, Hayden had moved on. The cursor was tracking the data flow again, the movement steady, the tremor absent.\n\n\"Any luck on the Reyes alias?\" she asked.\n\n\"Nothing clean. Just the old cardiac file. If they used a dead drop, it was paper and it's already gone.\" His voice was steady. \"We shift to the temporal logs. Cross-reference the insertion windows against known QSA maintenance schedules.\"\n\n\"Done,\" she said.\n\nShe sat down at the table and opened the secondary device. She overlaid the photograph of the corridor geometry with a blank vector field. She then pulled the most recent movement logs from the safe house’s passive optical system—the logs they maintained for security redundancy, showing ingress and egress patterns for both of them.\n\nShe pulled Hayden's log for the last seven days: twenty-one movements through the main corridor. She compared them, one by one, against the overlaid geometry.\n\nThe corridor log documented his pace, his weight distribution, and his lateral drift—the minute-by-minute, sub-conscious negotiation of his body with the narrow space. For the first nineteen entries, the log was clean: his body favored the left side of the corridor, his pace was consistent, his weight distribution symmetrical.\n\nThe twentieth entry—the one logged four hours after the cursor failure—showed a difference.\n\nThe pace was identical. The weight distribution was symmetrical. But the lateral drift was wrong. On the return trip from the bedroom to the living area, his body drifted six centimetres to the right, bumping the side table that sat against the wall. The log registered the impact as a single, high-frequency spike in the acoustic record, a sound she had interpreted at the time as a book being moved.\n\nShe looked at the acoustic data again. It was not a book. It was the soft thud of a hip bone striking wood.\n\nSix centimetres. The kind of deviation a person made when they were walking in the dark, or when they were walking with a cognitive disconnect between intention and execution. Hayden never walked in the dark.\n\nShe filed the anomaly under ICS-Anomaly (Proprioceptive).\n\nShe then cross-referenced the lateral drift event with the clock. 04:17.\n\nThat time had been accounted for. She had looked up when he entered the living area, asking if he needed anything, and he’d said no, just a comm check. She had filed it under routine and gone back to sleep.\n\nShe looked at the anomaly. Six centimetres. A tremor. A bump that was not a bump. Three facts, each one individually explicable, each one pointing in the same direction. She had been observing him for weeks, and she had filed every instance under the assumption that his body was failing.\n\nShe had failed to consider the second explanation: that his body was failing, and he was deliberately concealing the failure from her.\n\nShe closed the file. The logical path from 'he has a tremor' to 'he is lying' was not a single step. It was a climb. And she was now at the base of the mountain, looking up at the summit she had deliberately avoided looking at for four years.\n\nShe opened the private partition and navigated to the QSA archive access log. The log that contained every document Hayden had ever accessed using his full Level 5 clearance—the archive she had maintained for operational redundancy, not for auditing. The archive she had never used.\n\nShe typed the query: ICS Log \\- J. Hayden \\- Full. Decrypt.\n\nThe screen populated. She got as far as column six before she stopped.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 1: 96\\.\n\nShe cross-referenced it against the QSA baseline documentation she'd lifted from Hayden's operational archive eight months ago, when the tremor in his left hand started and he told her it was a nerve compression from the Southbank extraction. She'd believed him. She'd watched him ice the hand and filed it under physical maintenance and said nothing more about it, and let it go because she was a good partner and good partners did not audit each other's medical presentations.\n\nShe had been, she now understood, auditng everything except the thing that mattered.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 100: 71\\.\n\nShe kept reading. \n\nThe anomaly was in the timestamps.\n\nThat was what Bell had been tracking for six weeks, in the private partition she'd carved off the secondary comm device — the one Hayden thought she used for legacy network contacts, dead-drop scheduling, the administrative sediment of fieldwork. She did use it for those things. She also used it for this: a quiet, accumulating file of discrepancies she had not yet decided what to do with.\n\nShe was a good operational planner. She understood that the decision of what to do with a thing could wait until the shape of the thing was fully known. Premature conclusions were how people got killed on jobs. So she had been patient. She had built the file the way she built extraction routes — methodically, without attachment to any particular outcome, testing each data point against the adjacent ones until the geometry either resolved or it didn't.\n\nFor six weeks, it hadn't resolved. The timestamps kept failing the test.\n\nThe first one had been the Alfred entry log — a routine cross-reference she'd run against their safe house sequencing to verify the B-734 insertion window. Standard practice. She ran it the same way she ran everything, because good logistics required a complete picture and a complete picture required checking the pieces you already trusted as well as the ones you didn't. The Alfred entry log showed Hayden badging in at 02:17. The safe house departure log, which she had written herself, showed him leaving at 02:31. Fourteen minutes. The corridor from the safe house to the Alfred insertion point ran six minutes at a controlled pace. She had walked it herself in the third week, clocking the variables — foot traffic, door weight, the slight uphill grade on Punt Road that added twenty seconds in wet conditions.\n\nFourteen minutes left four unaccounted for.\n\nShe had filed it under *safe house exit delay* and moved on. There were three dozen variables in any insertion that could absorb four minutes — a comm check that ran long, a biometric rescan at the first secure door, a recalibration if the field readings were outside tolerance. She knew this. She also knew that Hayden logged every delay in the prep notes, and the prep notes for that insertion contained no delay notation.\n\nShe had photographed the prep notes and added them to the partition file.\n\nThat was the first one. The subsequent five weeks had produced eleven more — each one individually explicable, each one sitting within the range of normal operational variance, each one pointing in the same direction when you laid them end to end on a table and looked at the geometry from above.\n\nHayden was losing time. Not in the field — in transit, in the intervals between logged events, in the negative space of a schedule she had been reading without understanding what she was reading.\n\nThe Alfred Hospital prep file was the first one she'd pulled with full decryption access. Hayden managed the QSA-facing documentation; she managed the physical logistics, the safe house sequencing, the comm protocols. Their division of labour was clean and had been clean for four years. It had never occurred to her to look at the jump records directly. She'd seen the summaries. She'd seen what he showed her, which she now understood was not the same thing.\n\nThe decryption took forty seconds. The file populated in columns: jump number, date, target reality, duration, ICS pre-jump, ICS post-jump, recovery window, clinical notes.\n\nShe got as far as column six before she stopped.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 1: 96\\.\n\nShe cross-referenced it against the QSA baseline documentation she'd lifted from Hayden's operational archive eight months ago, when the tremor in his left hand started and he told her it was a nerve compression from the Southbank extraction. She'd believed him. She'd watched him ice the hand and filed it under *physical maintenance* and said nothing more about it, and let it go because she was a good partner and good partners did not audit each other's medical presentations.\n\nShe had been, she now understood, auditng everything except the thing that mattered.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 100: 71\\.\n\nShe kept reading.\n\nThe clinical notes began at jump 47 — brief, technical, the kind of shorthand that read like log entries from a mechanic rather than a man. *Residue latency increased 0.3 seconds. No functional impairment.* At jump 67: *Post-transition proprioceptive adjustment window extended to 140 seconds. Within acceptable parameters. Unreported.* At jump 89: *Reflection lag present, approximately 0.5 seconds in fluorescent environments. Unreported to QSA medical.* At jump 112: *Balance disruption, four seconds, left-side bias. Concurrent memory insertion, female subject, unknown origin. Duration: eleven seconds. Unreported.*\n\nShe stopped at jump 112\\. Went back. Read it again.\n\n*Female subject, unknown origin.*\n\nThe way he'd described the Bleed in the early months, returned to her now. When she'd asked him directly — sitting in the kitchen of the first safe house, the one in Fitzroy with the draughty sash windows, over coffee that had gone cold because they'd been talking too long. He'd said: *fragments, mostly. Environmental — a room you've been in, a smell, a sound. Nothing coherent. Nothing that stays.*\n\nShe had believed that too.\n\n*Unreported.* The word appeared eleven times in the first hundred and fifty entries. She counted them. She was the kind of person who counted things rather than estimating them, because estimates were how errors accumulated and accumulated errors were how operations failed. Eleven times. Eleven instances of information that had been generated, documented in his own hand, and withheld from the QSA medical division that was supposed to be monitoring his neurological integrity.\n\nWithheld from her.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 200: 58\\.\n\nBell's left hand rested flat on the table. She noted it without naming it. She didn't move it.\n\nJump 200's clinical notes ran longer than the others. The handwriting had changed — she was reading a physical scan of handwritten entries, and up to jump 199 the script was compressed, efficient, the same hand that annotated extraction routes and circled abort triggers and wrote corridor timings in the margins of floor plans. At jump 200 it loosened at the margins. Not dramatically. The letters were still formed correctly, still legible, still recognisably his. But the pressure was different — the pen moving faster, the ink pooling fractionally at the end of each stroke as though the hand had committed to a speed it couldn't quite sustain. The handwriting of a man writing faster than he wanted to think.\n\n*Memory insertion duration increasing. Fourteen seconds, consistent female subject, unknown apartment, winter light. Subject laughs at something I can't hear. ICS calculation: current trajectory projects threshold breach at approximately jump 340\\. Adjusted projection assumes continued anchor proximity. Anchor variable reduces bleed rate by estimated 23%. Departure of anchor variable would accelerate cascade. Current operational posture: maintain anchor proximity. Prioritise.*\n\nShe read it twice.\n\nThe third time she reached *anchor variable* the comm board on the near wall pulsed twice — soft amber, their check-in frequency. She had seventeen minutes left in her audit window. She had estimated twenty-five minutes for the full log. The check-in was three minutes early.\n\nShe looked up.\n\nThe Docklands extraction route was pinned to the ops board at eye level, laminated, the lines of her own geometry running clean and deliberate across the grid. She'd drafted it on a Tuesday in March, the week before the job, using the warehouse table and a physical stylus because some work needed to be done by hand to be done correctly. Three egress vectors, two abort triggers, four timing windows colour-coded by risk gradient. Hayden had sat across from her with a red marker and said *what about the tram corridor* and she'd said *no, it's too variable after nine PM* and he'd looked at the route for a long moment and then made two small corrections in the upper quadrant — shaved thirty seconds off the secondary abort, opened a third-choice corridor she hadn't considered — and said *just in case*.\n\nHis handwriting in the upper quadrant was present-tense. Functional. The handwriting of a man who trusted his own judgment and wanted her to trust it too.\n\nThe comm pulsed again.\n\nBell set the secondary device face-down on the table. She kept her eyes on the Docklands route. On the red annotations. On the *just in case* corridor in the upper quadrant that had, in fact, been the one they used when the primary abort failed at 21:47 and she'd said *secondary* and he'd already said *third* and they'd moved through it together without breaking stride, because they were good at this, because four years of shared fieldwork built something that worked even when it shouldn't, even in the dark, even when the geometry was bad and the timing was worse and the only thing holding the operation together was the fact that they had both been paying attention.\n\nShe picked up the comm device.\n\nShe said: \"Confirmed.\"\n\nFrom the bedroom — from wherever he was sitting with his back to the door the way he always sat, facing the window even when the window showed nothing, the habit of a man who had spent too many years needing to know what was outside: \"Holding.\"\n\nThe comm closed.\n\nShe held the Docklands route in her eyeline for the full thirty seconds their protocol required. His red ink in the upper quadrant. The *just in case* corridor. The two corrections that had saved the job. She looked at them and she did not look away, because the Docklands route was the last thing in the room that existed in the register she had understood it to exist in twenty minutes ago, and she understood, with the part of her that processed operational logistics before it processed anything else, that the moment she looked away from it the room would never be the same configuration again.\n\nThirty seconds.\n\nShe put the comm device down and turned the secondary device face-up and kept reading.\n\nICS post-jump, jump 300: 49\\.\n\nClinical note, jump 300: *Severe erosion threshold breached. Functional impairment: intermittent. Proprioceptive confusion, 3-8 seconds per episode, frequency increasing. Tremor present and persistent in left hand. Pharmacological protocol initiated. Neuroinhibitor dosing: prophylactic, daily. Procurement: independent, untraceable. Anchor variable still present. Bleed rate: managed. Recommend no operational changes. Recommend continued non-disclosure to anchor variable.*\n\nShe thought about the fourteen-minute gap in the Alfred entry log. The four unaccounted minutes. She had walked the corridor herself and clocked the variables and filed the discrepancy under *safe house exit delay* because there were always variables in an insertion and she had trusted his prep notes.\n\nThe prep notes had not mentioned a balance disruption. Had not mentioned proprioceptive confusion. Had not mentioned that his legs had been unreliable for six months and that he had been managing it alone, without telling her, because telling her would trigger departure and departure would accelerate cascade and he had run the calculation six times and decided the cost of disclosure was too high.\n\nShe kept reading.\n\nJump 340's entry changed the character of the handwriting permanently. She'd been watching for it since jump 200\\. She found it in the upper-right notation of a page otherwise identical to the preceding ones — a small, corrective bracket around the phrase *cognitive integrity* that suggested he'd written it, stopped, considered striking it, and decided to leave it. The bracket was tight, precise, a habit of self-correction she had seen in every floor plan he'd ever annotated. He had written the phrase, doubted it, and chosen honesty over revision.\n\nBelow the bracket, in smaller script: *ICS 41\\. The man who started this log would not recognise the calculus I am currently running. I find I don't have an opinion about that.*\n\nShe sat with that sentence for longer than she sat with any of the others.\n\nThe man who started this log. As though he were filing a report on someone he had known well and had since lost contact with. As though the distance between jump 1 and jump 340 were not a timeline but a translation — one language becoming another, the original no longer recoverable without a key he no longer possessed.\n\n*I find I don't have an opinion about that.*\n\nThat was the line that told her everything the clinical shorthand hadn't. Not the ICS numbers, not the bleed multipliers, not the pharmacological procurement protocol. The absence of opinion. A man who had documented his own dissolution across three hundred and forty jumps and had arrived, at the far end of it, at a place where the dissolution no longer registered as loss.\n\nJump 380: ICS 34\\. The clinical notes at jump 380 occupied a full page. She read them slowly, at the pace she read floor plans when the stakes were high — every word, every notation, nothing skimmed.\n\n*Continuous tremor now bilateral. Balance disruption frequency: daily. Memory insertion duration: up to 47 seconds. Insertions now include sensory data — temperature, scent, ambient sound. Female subject consistent across all insertions. Apartment consistent. Winter light. She laughs at something. I still can't hear it.*\n\n*ICS trajectory: terminal within 60-90 jumps absent intervention. Pharmacological management extending window. Anchor proximity: still primary mitigation variable. I have run the calculation. Without anchor proximity, current trajectory projects full cascade within 14-20 jumps. With anchor proximity, window extends to 40-55 jumps. Difference: 21-35 jumps.*\n\n*I require the window. The mission requires the window. Continued non-disclosure assessed as operationally necessary. Anchor variable's awareness of clinical status would trigger departure and accelerate cascade. Assessment: the cost of disclosure outweighs the cost of non-disclosure.*\n\nThe calculus was clean. It was a perfectly executed piece of institutional logic, and it was devastating not because it was wrong, but because it was accurate. She ran the numbers again: 21-35 jumps. That was the window she provided. Every time she sat in the chair across from him, every time she made coffee in the morning, every time she looked at him and said nothing about the tremor, she was performing an operational function. She was a physical boundary, a neurological shield, a necessary component—not a partner. Hayden had spent four years defining their relationship in clinical terms, calculating the cost of her awareness against the cost of his life. The professional cruelty of it was a pressure on her sternum, a feeling of mass that did not belong there. He had not lied about the job; he had lied about the physics of their connection. He had chosen the quantifiable asset over the unquantifiable human, and the log was the proof that the choice had been made, documented, and filed without a single internal expression of regret. He hadn’t simply kept a secret; he had made her one. She was the one who had run the logistics, who had set the safe house grid, who had believed their four years together represented a shared commitment, and all of it, every minute, had been an equation running toward a single, clinical truth: Bell’s utility was maximized by her ignorance. She closed her eyes. The thought was sharp: he had traded her integrity for thirty-five jumps, and he had slept well every night knowing the transaction was complete.  \nHe had run it six times. It was accurate.\n\nBell set the device flat on the table and looked at the wall above the ops board. The blank section of wall to the left of the Docklands route where she'd taken down the safe house grid last week when the third location went dark. The rectangle of slightly less faded paint where it had hung. She had taken it down because the safe house was no longer relevant, and she had replaced it with nothing because there had been nothing ready to replace it with, and she had looked at that rectangle of paler paint every day since and not registered it as anything except a scheduling gap.\n\nShe registered it now as space she would need to move through on her way out.\n\nShe picked the device back up.\n\nJump 417\\. Three days ago.\n\nICS post-jump: 32\\.\n\nThe clinical note at jump 417 was four words.\n\n*I can't hear her.*",
