          "text": "The shower's water temperature control was a manual dial — a heritage fitting that the building had retained during the 2139 construction because the developer had been selling the apartments on the basis of their period detailing. The dial ran from blue to red, with Chen's preferred setting marked by a faint calcium deposit at the seven-o'clock position — the accumulated residue of nine years of the same temperature, the same duration, the same hand reaching for the same point on the dial.\n\nThe QSA's passive monitoring had flagged the shower duration anomaly: fourteen minutes, up from Chen's established average of eight. The forensic team had noted it. Their report had classified it as a lifestyle variation.\n\nKain looked at the dial.\n\nThe calcium deposit was at the seven-o'clock position. The dial's current setting — where it had been left, last used — was at nine o'clock. Warmer. The replacement ran the shower hotter than Chen had. Not dramatically hotter. Two positions on a dial. The kind of difference that registered as preference rather than discontinuity.\n\nBut the fourteen minutes was not about preference. The replacement ran the shower for fourteen minutes because it needed fourteen minutes. Eight minutes had been sufficient for Chen because Chen had been washing a body he had inhabited for fifty-one years and knew with the automatic efficiency of long familiarity. The replacement needed the additional six minutes because it was washing a body it was still learning — still checking, still mapping, still running its hands across the surface of a physical form that was not its original and that it had not yet made automatic.\n\nFourteen minutes was the duration of a replacement that had not yet stopped being careful.\n\nHe left the bathroom and crossed to the desk.",
