          "title": "Scene 2",
          "text": "He had perhaps eight minutes before the third Coherence Failure. The third, at this buffer level, would not be 2.3 seconds or 3.1 seconds. The clinical file's data on Coherence Failure duration at sub-20% buffer efficiency showed a non-linear escalation. The third event would be longer. Longer meant a greater risk of the failure becoming self-sustaining — the binding sites losing the capacity to re-establish their dissipation function between events, the Bleeds beginning to chain rather than resolve.\n\nHe picked up the journals.\n\nAll six. The stack was heavier than it looked — the institutional notebooks were the thick-paged kind, the kind designed for field conditions, and fourteen months of Emily's notation filled them completely. He held them against his chest with both arms, the way a man carries something he does not intend to put down.\n\nEmily watched him do this without moving.\n\n\"The sweep teams are in the building,\" she said. \"Ground floor and sublevel 1\\. I have not called them to the second floor.\"\n\n\"Why.\"\n\n\"Because I need you to understand the calculus before you make a decision that cannot be unmade.\" Her voice was still level. Still clinical. But underneath the clinical register — not emotion, not guilt, but the specific quality of a person who has been carrying a weight for fourteen months and has decided that the carrying is finished. \"The Sphere mapping is 94% complete. Eleven deployments. Deployment twelve closes the gap. With a complete map, the QSA can predict convergence events eighteen months in advance. Eighteen months of lead time means evacuation, containment, zero civilian casualties. It means the replacement network becomes unnecessary. It means Winters goes home.\" A pause. \"It means the next PQ carrier the QSA identifies does not get deployed at all, because the map is complete and the baseline data is no longer required.\"\n\n\"One more deployment.\"\n\n\"One more deployment.\"\n\nThe room was very quiet. The Atmospheric Entanglement Field produced no sound — its presence was entirely proprioceptive, entirely neurological, the thickened air and the anterior pressure and the binding sites consuming their last reserves of dissipation capacity. Outside the window, the Punt Road traffic moved in the ordinary way of a Tuesday morning in a city that did not know what was happening in the buildings it passed.\n\n\"The journals contain the mapping data,\" Kain said.\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"If I take them, the mapping data leaves the QSA's custody.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"And if the mapping data leaves the QSA's custody, deployment twelve becomes the QSA's only path to completing the map.\"\n\nEmily said nothing. Which was the answer.\n\nHe looked at the journals in his arms. Fourteen months of his own degradation, recorded in blue ink in Emily's precise notation. Fourteen months of resonance data — his neural architecture, his buffer efficiency, his Bleed episodes, his ICS readings — compiled into the most complete map of the Sphere's coherence structure the QSA had ever produced. Ninety-four percent complete.\n\nSix percent remaining.\n\nOne deployment.\n\nThe tactical pivot was not a decision made in the room. It was a decision that had been made in the plant room at the Fitzroy Library, in the moment the terminal's screen went dark and the last paragraph of Section 3 sat in his working memory with the number 11 against the number 14 and the gap of three deployments between them. The decision had been made then. What was happening in this room was not the making of the decision but the execution of it — the specific, operational process of converting a decision into a set of actions that could not be reversed.\n\n\"The sweep teams,\" he said.\n\n\"Ground floor and sublevel 1.\"\n\n\"The freight lift.\"\n\n\"Is still keyed.\"\n\nHe looked at her for two seconds. The look was not accusation and it was not gratitude and it was not the look of a man saying goodbye to a person who had used him. It was the look of a man updating his model of the environment he was operating in, for what might be the last time, with the specific, exhausted attention of someone who has been running the model for eleven deployments and has finally identified the variable that was never in it.\n\nShe had left the journals on the desk.\n\nShe had not called the sweep teams to the second floor.\n\nThe calculus was not complicated. But it was not the calculus she had described.\n\nHe walked to the door.\n\n\"Kain.\"\n\nHe stopped. Did not turn.\n\n\"The field resets in four minutes,\" Emily said. \"At your current buffer level, a reset event will produce a Coherence Failure you will not recover from in the corridor. You need to be in the lift before the reset.\"\n\nFour minutes.\n\nHe walked.\n\n\\*\\*\\*\n\nThe freight lift doors closed at the two-minute mark.\n\nThe Atmospheric Entanglement Field reset at the three-minute mark—a pressure shift he felt even through the lift’s steel shell. The anterior push vanished all at once. Then came the silence in the binding sites. Not relief—something worse. The ominous quiet of a system driven to the edge and suddenly cut to black. The binding sites weren’t recovering. They were simply no longer being pressed. \n\nThe difference between those two states was the difference between a man who had stopped bleeding and a man whose blood pressure had dropped too low to bleed.\n\nThe lift reached the ground floor.\n\nThe medical waste corridor was empty. The Pelco unit above the waste bay's vehicle entrance was still angled at 34 degrees from vertical. The pedestrian door opened in 0.8 seconds. The heritage plane trees' canopy covered the lane's middle forty metres.\n\nHe walked south on Punt Road with the journals under his arm and the binding sites quiet in the specific way of a system that had reached its limit and was waiting, with the patience of a biological process rather than a human one, to see what happened next.\n\nHis phone was on a tram somewhere north of the city.\n\nEmily had not called the sweep teams to the second floor.\n\nThe journals were in his arms.\n\nNinety-four percent of a map that could end the replacement network, retire the baseline protocol, and send Winters home to Ballarat.\n\nSix percent remaining.\n\nHe walked.",
