          "text": "\"The SEP-NULL is not a location in standard space. It is the geometric centre of the Sphere's entanglement field, which exists in a superposition of spatial coordinates — it occupies a fixed point relative to the Sphere's own coherence structure, not relative to any external reference frame.\" Hayden's right hand broke free of the left and moved to the chair's armrest, gripping it with the force of a hand that had learned to use external surfaces as a substitute for internal stability. \"To reach the SEP-NULL, a carrier must initiate a transition from within the Sphere's 0.3-radii threshold. The transition is not a jump in the standard sense — it is a coherence collapse. The carrier's ICS drops below the minimum threshold for identity maintenance, and the carrier's neural architecture is pulled toward the nearest coherence singularity, which at that distance is the SEP-NULL.\"\n\n\"A controlled ICS collapse.\"\n\n\"A directed one.\" Hayden looked at his right hand on the armrest. At the tremor in it. \"The carrier must be coherent enough to direct the collapse toward the SEP-NULL rather than allowing it to fragment randomly. Which requires an ICS above approximately 40 at the moment of initiation.\" He looked up. \"My ICS is 32 and dropping. I cannot direct the collapse. I would fragment before I reached the threshold.\"\n\nThe number sat in the room with the biophotonic field and the pooling light and the fracture in the plaster and the fifty-one minutes of power and the thirty-three minutes of intact plaster and the two terminal carriers on different points of the same degradation curve, one of them with an ICS of 32 and dropping and one of them with an ICS that the clinical file had last measured at 71 and that the stress of the past four hours had reduced by approximately twelve points.\n\nFifty-nine.\n\nAbove 40\\.\n\nKain pressed his shoulders harder against the wall. The anterior pressure behind the orbital ridge had been constant for forty minutes — not spiking, not receding, holding at the level it had reached when he entered the room and the combined field had established its entrainment plateau. The binding sites were cycling through their degraded dissipation function at a rate that was consuming their remaining capacity in the specific, measurable way of a system operating at maximum load with no recovery interval.\n\nHe had been in the room for forty minutes.\n\nAt 3 ICS points per hour under sustained field exposure, he had lost two points since entering.\n\nCurrent estimate: 57\\.\n\nStill above 40\\.\n\nThe margin was not comfortable. The margin was a number, and numbers changed, and the rate at which this number was changing was a function of how long he remained in a room where two terminal PQ carriers were generating a combined biophotonic field at entrainment plateau.\n\nHe looked at the fifth journal in his hands. At the transition coordinates on pages 31 through 47\\. At the full logistical architecture of a jump that Emily had been designing for fourteen months, compiled from eleven deployments of resonance data, refined across six journals of off-network notation.\n\n\"There is one variable she did not account for,\" Hayden said.\n\nKain looked up from the journal.\n\nHayden's outline was stuttering continuously now — not the double-beat or the triple-beat but a sustained, high-frequency oscillation, the boundary between his body and the room's air moving faster than the eye could resolve into discrete positions. The long-exposure effect had intensified to the point where his edges were not a line but a region — a zone of spatial uncertainty two to three centimetres wide in which Hayden's body was simultaneously present and not present, the quantum superposition of a man whose identity architecture had lost the coherence required to maintain a fixed boundary between himself and the world.\n\nBell had been gone for six hours.\n\n\"She designed the deployment sequence,\" Hayden said, \"to produce a carrier who would complete the map because the QSA directed him to. She did not design it to produce a carrier who had read the file, taken the journals, walked out of the hospital, and arrived at this address under his own operational logic.\" A pause. The oscillating pupils completed a full cycle. \"She built an instrument. She did not account for the instrument deciding.\"\n\nThe room's biophotonic field pressed against the walls. The fracture in the plaster extended another millimetre. The light pooled in the corners with the specific, unphysical density of a field that had been accumulating for six hours in Hayden's case and forty minutes in Kain's, and the two accumulations had entrained into a single field that was larger than either of them had been separately, and the room was smaller than the field required, and the plaster was registering this fact in the only language available to it.\n\nKain looked at the transition coordinates on page 31\\.\n\nAt the SEP-NULL designation at the diagram's centre.\n\nAt the 40-second window and the instantaneous buffer saturation and the irreversible neural integration that the QSA's clinical file did not have a retirement designation for.\n\nAt the 6% gap in the most complete map of the Sphere's coherence structure the QSA had ever produced.\n\nAt the number 57, declining at 3 points per hour. Forty-nine minutes of power remaining in a building the civic layer had already forgotten existed. Thirty-one minutes of intact plaster. A fracture extending at one millimetre every four minutes. A man in a chair whose outline was no longer a line but a region. Six journals on the floor containing fourteen months of his own degradation, recorded in blue ink by a woman who had designed the instrument for the specific task and had not accounted for the instrument deciding. \n\nThe instrument, deciding.\n\n#",
